<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing to Close Toronto Plant in Late 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Aerospace giant Boeing Co. is
expected to close its Toronto area plant in late 1999 with the
loss of more than 2,000 highly skilled jobs, the Globe and Mail
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There has been no official decision to close the plant. But
George Capern, president of the Canadian division, has confirmed
that it is "the logical conclusion."
</P>
<P>
Boeing has almost twice the factory space it needs following
its purchase of the McDonnell Douglas Corp. last year, which owned
the Toronto plant.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is picking the best plant from each company and closing
the rest. There is nothing that can be done to save the plant,
Capern said.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto plant was one of the most important in the
McDonnell Douglas aviation empire. It made the wings for every
DC-8, DC-9 and DC-10 jetliner in the world, and for the newer
equivalents of the latter two.
</P>
<P>
After the merger, Boeing decided to cut production of most
McDonnell Douglas aircraft and close the plants they were made in.
</P>
<P>
The company has already announced that the production of the
MD-80 and MD-90 jetliners will end early next year with the loss
of 800 Toronto-area jobs.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the MD-11 would die in late 1999, ending jobs
for another 600 Canadian workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
