<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Vehicle Sales Jump in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The sales of cars and trucks in
the United States surpassed 1.5 million in May, a 12.1 percent
rise over the same month last year, the New York Times said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Car sales went up 6.9 percent while light-truck sales rose 18.4
percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Fueled by hefty price cuts, the seasonally adjusted annual
selling rate for light vehicles reached 16.3 million cars and
trucks in the year to last month, the highest level since October
1987.
</P>
<P>
Sales were driven up also by attractive incentive programs.
Automakers spent as much as 1,600 U.S. dollars a vehicle on
incentives in May, up from about 1,100 dollars a year ago,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In mid-April, General Motors sent certificates worth 500 to
1,000 dollars to previous buyers of G.M. products for the purchase
50 different models, above and beyond other cash rebates and
low-interest loan incentives.
</P>
<P>
General Motors said Thursday that its sales of cars and trucks
grew by 12.4 percent compared with May 1997, with truck sales up
by 19.2 percent and cars by seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Ford reported a 1.2 percent growth in the sales of cars and
trucks in the year to May 1997, with its car sales falling by by
5.5 percent but truck sales soaring by 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler said Tuesday that it had its best month yet in May,
selling 250,031 cars and trucks, a 27 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
Japanese and German automakers also reported strong sales in
the U.S. in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
