<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho's Former FM Offered Deputy Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's former foreign
minister, Kelebone Maope, who was surprisingly excluded from
Lesotho's new cabinet, has been offered the position of deputy
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"I have been offered this position and there is a likelihood
that I will be joining cabinet next week," South African Press
Association (SAPA) Thursday quoted Maope as saying in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
Another surprise exclusion, former prime minister Ntsu
Mokhehle's brother Shakhane, has been offered the portfolio of
works and transport, and he is likely to accept it soon, said
SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Maope and Mokhehle were excluded from the cabinet announced by
Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili on Wednesday, apparently
because they declined ministerial posts in protest against
certain appointments to the cabinet, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted a source close to Maope and Mokhehle as saying
that they were not happy with the suggested composition of the
cabinet and the lack of consultation by the prime minister in the
process of appointing ministers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Mosisili said a deputy prime minister had
not been appointed yet as he was still consulting on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Two portfolios -- works and transport and agriculture,
cooperatives and land reclamation -- had also not been filled but
the matter was receiving attention, Mosisili said.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen cabinet ministers were sworn in Thursday morning by
Chief Justice Joseph Kheola in the presence of King Letsie III.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet was formed after the ruling LCD won a sweeping
victory in the mountain kingdom's May 23 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Ailing former prime minister Ntsu Mokhehle announced
resignation on May 28, paving the way for Mosisili, Mokhehle's
deputy, to step into his shoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
