<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vote May Be Called on Israeli-Palestinian Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Thursday that progress has been made towards a
redeployment agreement with the Palestinians, and he did not rule
out the possibility of a referendum on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat are "very
close" toward an agreement on Israeli pullback from the West Bank
in order to revive the peace process, informed sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that despite the
progress, he did not know when and if an agreement would be
signed. Meanwhile, he dismissed as "out of date" Israeli press
reports on a revised United States proposal.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Netanyahu did not rule out the possibility of
presenting the agreement for a referendum, which was called for by
far-right wingers in his Likud coalition.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kleiner, head of the extremist Knesset (Parliament)
group Land of Israel Front, demanded that Netanyahu "go to the
people" with any redeployment agreement he reached with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
A deal may be "nearer than any one thinks," he said. If so, the
right wing will commit itself to voting no-confidence on the prime
minister, he warned.
</P>
<P>
But his idea for a referendum was categorically rejected by
coalition whip Meir Shetrit. There is no need for a referendum
since it would only postpone the actual progress in the talks, he
said. "It is quite clear that most of the people in Israel would
like to see the peace process going on," he added.
</P>
<P>
An agreement with the Palestinians will undoubtedly be approved
by the Knesset "by a large majority," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shetrit acknowledged that the coalition is likely to fall
apart over this issue but stressed that "this is the risk we must
take."
</P>
<P>
Sources have said that Netanyahu was trying to combine the
three stages of redeployment into a 15 percent pullback, and if it
was accepted by the U.S. and the Palestinians, he would make
further concessions.
</P>
<P>
But according to the reported U.S. proposal, in a period of 12
weeks divided into three phases, 12 percent of Israeli controlled
territory Area C will go to jointly controlled Area B; 1 percent
of Area C will go to Area A under Palestinian control; and an
additional 14.2 percent of Area B will go to Area A.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported earlier Thursday that U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross was holding talks in London with senior Palestinian
officials Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) and Ahmed Queria (Abu Ala)
over the revised U.S. proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
