<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Business Sees Benefit In Improving Employability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- British firms recognize that
providing more on-the-job training helps productivity and
encourages staff to remain with the company.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two thirds of firms already train employees beyond the
needs of their current job, according to the latest edition of CBI
News (Confederation of British Industry).
</P>
<P>
Initial findings by a major CBI survey, Employment Trends, have
found that increasing employees' employability can have benefit in
terms of better skills, adaptability, motivation, and retention of
staff.
</P>
<P>
The survey findings also reveal that companies'working patterns
are becoming more flexible. Forty-one percent of firms are using
more contract workers, 47 per cent more temporary staff, and 38
per cent more flexible working hours.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four percent of organizations have also reported that
they feel that job security has decreased over the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the findings, Adair Turner, CBI Director General,
said: "These changes towards greater flexibility have been vital
to the UK's improved record on unemployment."
</P>
<P>
"Individuals' confidence in their own employability is the key
antidote to job insecurity, enabling them to see labor market
flexibility as liberating rather than threatening," he added.
</P>
<P>
CBI identifies three key "interests vitally concerned with
achieving employability":
</P>
<P>
- The individual: it is individuals who are or become
employable and an "employable individual has the qualities and
competencies that employers need.
</P>
<P>
- Society: Increased employability is key to helping flexible
labor markets work effectively, leading to both higher potential
growth and greater social cohesion.
</P>
<P>
- Business interest: Companies that focus on employees'
employability can benefit from having, among other things,a better
skilled, productive and adaptable workforce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
