<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade on Zimbabwean Stock Market Remains Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Trade in key industrial shares on
the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange, the second largest one in Africa,
Thursday remained firm, pushing the index 54 points up to 7,436.
</P>
<P>
The market has been bullish for the past four days on the back
of firming tobacco prices which are helping to stablize the
Zimbabwean Dollar, and this week's release of the first tranche
of a 176 million U.S. Dollars stand-by balance of payment support
by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
In minings, the index lost 41 points to close at 369.
</P>
<P>
But brokers were cautious about the market's recovery, saying
it was fragile and would not be sustainable, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We do not think this is sustainable because in mid-July we
are likely to witness hostile wage negotiations which might put a
dent on the current rally," said an analyst from Quincor James
Capel Stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
"There is also an overhanging fuel price hike which will
obviously trigger a wave of price increases in other
commodities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Doubts emerged in the market about the government's
ability to meet the stringent targets tied to the IMF aid,
raising fears that the country may fail to secure the remaining
tranches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
