<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Panel Soon to Probe into Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- An international panel set up
by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) is to visit Rwanda
soon for investigation into the 1994 genocide in that country,
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The panel will also attend a solemn ceremony in memory of the
victims of the genocide after arriving in Rwanda, Salim told the
68th ordinary session of the OAU council of ministers opened here
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief announced Wednesday the composition of the
7-member international panel of eminent personalities, three of
whom are from outside Africa, to investigate the 1994 genocide in
Rwanda and surrounding events.
</P>
<P>
It will also visit other countries of the Great Lakes region
and elsewhere as appropriate, said Salim, who is here to attend
the coming OAU summit scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
He therefore appealed to member states and all other states
and institutions concerned to extend full cooperation to the
panel to enable it to discharge its important responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed," said Salim, "the knowledge of what went wrong and
what was not done to prevent the genocide in Rwanda in 1994, is
critical for us, particularly as part of our efforts to prevent
future occurrence of a tragedy of such magnitude."
</P>
<P>
"For the Great Lakes Region, this is absolutely essential as
we continue to receive very disturbing news of the killings and
massacres of innocent people by some of those who are believed to
have been involved in the planning and execution of the genocide
in Rwanda," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the OAU chief, the investigation will address,
among other things, issues such as the root cause of the genocide
in Rwanda, the circumstances in which the genocide took place and
its consequences in Rwanda and the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The roles of states and non-state actors before, during and
after the genocide will also be included in the investigation to
be carried out by the panel, scheduled for inauguration this
September.
</P>
<P>
A special trust fund was also established to support the work
of the panel and ensure its independence, while the establishment
of a panel support group made up of experts and advisors from a
multi-disciplinary background and with the requisite knowledge and
experience of the region is underway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
