<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Helps Zimbabwe Clear Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Defense Minister Moven
Mahachi Thursday commissioned demining equipment worth more than
500,000 U.S. Dollars which was donated by the U.S. government for
clearing mines in areas around Victoria Falls.
</P>
<P>
A joint demining training exercise between the U.S. and
Zimbabwean engineering troops started in Victoria Falls in west
Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi said landmine problems in Zimbabwe continued to claim
lives of innocent civilians 18 years after independence and
government efforts to undertake the clearing exercise had been
impaired by the meager financial resources.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Attache Majes Cobb said the U.S. government's
object was to assist Zimbabwe in establishing a fully functional
demining office.
</P>
<P>
"We are providing the resources and technology that will
facilitate the expansion of what has already been a very
successful command center of the Zimbabwe national army," Cobb
said.
</P>
<P>
The Victoria Falls area is one of the largest tourist
attractions infested with mines which were planted by Rhodesian
and South African forces during the struggle for Zimbabwe's
independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
