<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Enjoys High Degree Autonomy: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of China's Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) said here Thursday that
the HKSAR has been enjoying a high degree of autonomy and freedom
on issues unrelated to defense and foreign affairs after its
handover to China last July.
</P>
<P>
"I'm delighted to tell you without any hesitation the political
transition has certainly gone very, very well," Anson Chan, Chief
Secretary for Administration of the HKSAR, said in a speech at the
Japan National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
Attributing the region's sluggish economy to a "contagion
effect" from the Asian crisis, Chan said that the HKSAR will
continue to take measures to revitalize business, adding that
medium-and long-term prospects remain excellent because of solid
economic fundamentals and abundant foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong also continues to benefit as the gateway of the
strong mainland economy, which "has remained immune so far" to the
Asian crisis, she said.
</P>
<P>
As for Japan, Chan urged Tokyo to revitalize its weak economy
and play a key role in helping Asian economies recover from their
year-long financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and other Asian nations are looking for signs of
Japan's economic recovery as the "key player and the largest
creditor," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Chan, who is in Tokyo to promote tourism, said the HKSAR would
take several measures including cheaper hotel costs to encourage
Japanese tourists to return there.
</P>
<P>
Japanese tourists, one of the major sources of Hong Kong's
economic growth, have declined sharply in number over the past
year following a big tour boom before Hong Kong's reversion last
year.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR lanuched a tourism promotion campaign in Tokyo this
week. The campaign, entitled "Hong Kong: New Era, New
Opportunities," includes a fashion show and a week-long festival
featuring Hong Kong products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
