<HEADLINE> Kurils No Hinder to Russian Ties: Japanese Admiral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Japanese Chairman of
the Council of Joint Chiefs of Staff, Admiral Kazuya Natsukawa,
Thursday expressed confidence that the territorial dispute over
the Kuril Islands with Russia would not hinder the bilateral
partnership.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, the Japanese admiral said Russia
and Japan could broaden military ties disregarding the issues of
disputed territories and the conclusion of a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Natsukawa said the strategic importance of the Kuril Islands
depends on the situation in the region. "Therefore, we must forge
trust to rule out conflict situations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Broader bilateral military contacts exerted a positive
influence not only in the Asia-Pacific region, but worldwide, the
Japanese officer said.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, it was premature to speak of a Russian-Japanese
strategic partnership. He said the strategic partnership could
evolve as a result of efforts made by the Asian Pacific countries
to enhance regional security.
</P>
<P>
Natsukawa also denied a claim that Japan intends to buy Russian
Sukhoi Su-27 fighter jets for its defense forces.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, two Japanese pilots who had been trained to
fly Su-27 fighters in Russia this spring praised the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Natsukawa arrived in Moscow on May 30 for an eight-day official
visit. He has met Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and Chief
of General Staff Anatoly Kvashnin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
