<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Visits Site of Train Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Thursday
travelled to the northern German town of Eschede to see himself
the site of the worst-ever German train crash which killed at
least 92 people so far.
</P>
<P>
Deeply depressed by the tragedy, Kohl pledged that the federal
government would make all efforts to help the victims.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who cut short a visit to Italy after knowing of the
accident, also warned against making premature judgements about
the cause of the train crash before thorough investigations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the German rail authorities has put a temporary
speed limit of 160 kilometers an hour on all ICE high speed trains
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The ICE train involved in the crash on Wednesday was travelling
at about 200 kilometers an hour when it suddenly derailed and
slammed into a road bridge at Eschede.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers using five heavy cranes started to lift a final
huge chunk of the collapsed bridge from two train carriages still
buried under the debris. More victims are feared to be trapped in
the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
The German Red Cross officials said that over 20,000 people had
followed an appeal and turned out to donate blood for those
injured during the crash. The latest official reports said that
there were 58 people still being treated in hospitals, 43 of them
with serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
The disaster also aroused shocks around the world with
condolence messages continuing to pour in on Thursday. Flags at
public buildings in Germany are flying at half mask to mourn the
victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
