<HEADLINE> Demirel Asks Chirac to Correct Legislature's Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
Thursday sent a letter to his French counterpart Jacques Chirac,
asking him to use his power to correct French legislature's draft
law on the alleged Armenian genocide.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan
at a weekly press conference here. Demirel in his letter said he
would express the views of the Turkish side concerning the bill
adopted by France's National Assembly on May 29, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, French lawmakers unanimously approved the bill
stating that "France publicly recognizes the Armenian genocide of
1915."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has denied that the deaths of some 1.5 million
Armenians in Ottoman Turkey between 1915 and 1923 constituted a
genocide, insisting that massacres occurred on both sides as the
result of a civil war.
</P>
<P>
"We know that there are sad events in the history of all
countries," Demirel told Chirac in his letter.
</P>
<P>
"It is a historical reality that both Turkish and Armenian
people died during the revolt and violence of the Armenian side
against the Ottoman Empire," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added this was because of "foreign provocations in 1915 and
consequently the efforts for trying to locate the Armenians in the
regions not engaged in the First World War."
</P>
<P>
He warned that the bill of the French National Assembly has the
attribute of provoking terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
"This bill, which offended both Turkey and nearly 300,000
Turkish people living in France, won't be useful for anyone except
those who want to disturb the improving Turkish-French relations
and the establishment of peace and stability in the Caucasus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
