<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Trade Ties Good for Both: U.S. Business Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Economic and trade relations
between the United States and China are important and have already
generated great benefits for both countries, although there is
still room for improvement, says an American business leader.
</P>
<P>
In a recent telephone interview, Robert A. Kapp, president of
the U.S.-China Business Council, said he believed that business
and economic matters will certainly, and should be, on the agenda in
the forthcoming Beijing summit between U.S. President Bill Clinton
and his Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's China visit scheduled for late June, the first by a
U.S. president in nearly a decade, is a chance to continue the
process of building a stronger relationship between the United
States and China, Kapp said.
</P>
<P>
On many fronts, the process cannot be completed by the visit,
but, "we should benefit from the return visit by the president to
China following President Jiang's visit here last October," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We see this visit as an important block in the construction of
a larger structure which will continue to be built in the long
years after the president's visit," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kapp said he assumed that the two presidents will have an
opportunity to discuss all of the essential ingredients of the
successful relationship between the two countries, of the points
the two sides agree on and the points they do not agree on.
</P>
<P>
Trade is a point on which the two sides agree and disagree,
said Kapp, who became council chairman in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Neither side would deny that the economic and trade relations
between the two countries are important and have already generated
great benefit for both countries," he said. "But also, neither
side would deny that the trade relations today are not all they
should be," he said. "There is room for improvement in economic
and trade relations between our two countries."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Trade Ties Good for Both: U.S. Business Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kapp said the two sides have had extensive discussions about
the possibility of concluding individual commercial transactions
either before or during the visit, some of which would involve
opportunities for American companies to create sizable sales with
China.
</P>
<P>
"We hope these transactions might be concluded," said Kapp,
whose council represent more than 300 American businesses. But, he
said, the signals are still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
On China's accession to the WTO, Kapp said he believed that
intensive negotiations have taken place on many aspects to the WTO
question in recent months.
</P>
<P>
"But so far we don't see clear evidence of enough agreement on
enough questions between the two sides as to be able to be sure
that the summit will have a meaningful statement on this subject."
</P>
<P>
"We very much hope that there will be," he said, but there had
not been enough progress to justify that statement.
</P>
<P>
Asked about China's most favored nation (MFN) trade status,
Kapp said regrettably neither American friends nor China should
take MFN for granted.
</P>
<P>
He said he had anticipated that there would be some bombshell,
some explosion of controversy over the U.S.-China relations in the
United States either before the president's visit, or before the
annual MFN decision, or both, and it's no secret that that
bombshell has now burst.
</P>
<P>
However, Kapp said he was "reasonably confident", China's MFN
status will be retained, but it will again be the subject of
heated controversy.
</P>
<P>
Referring to allegations involving satellite technology, Kapp
said many different questions and problems have been merged
together into a single controversy.
</P>
<P>
There is only a leaked story, he said. That matter needs to be
cleared up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
