<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Trade Ties Good for Both: U.S. Business Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kapp said he thought the discussions in the American congress
certainly has elements of American domestic politics which
certainly caused a heightened level of controversy surrounding the
president's trip to China.
</P>
<P>
"I find the whole thing regrettable and we, as the business
community, are very concerned about the casual acceptance of the
allegations as facts. But at the same time, it is impossible to
pretend that the controversy does not exist. And it would be
necessary to find as quickly as possible a clear fact on the most
difficult aspects of this," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kapp said the he thought the two governments should be prepared
to take reciprocal and unilateral steps to meet the concern of the
other side.
</P>
<P>
It is not always necessary to have a big fight to have one side
lose and the other side win, he said. "In fact that would never
happen." But there is room for each side to take decisions on
their own sovereignty without being told to do so by the other
side. That will make a real contribution to a better relationship.
</P>
<P>
The two governments are now in good if rather formal contact
with each other, Kapp said. In addition, one hopes that in spite
of all the political controversies, each government will be able
to take unilateral measures in response perhaps to the unilateral
measures taken by the other side to remove some of the inherent
and difficult issues on the table. "That is my greatest hope," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kapp expressed the hope that the visit of President Clinton to
China will be an opportunity for many Americans, through
television, to get to know more about China.
</P>
<P>
Describing China as an "immense and complex reality", Kapp said
he hoped President Clinton's visit will serve as an occasion for
many Americans to become a little bit more broadly informed about
life today in China. 
</P>
