<HEADLINE> IPE Proposes Complete Overhaul Of Electricity Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Petroleum Exchange
(IPE) Thursday proposed to the UK Government a thorough
restructuring of the electricity market in order to ensure that
consumers pay a fair price for their supplies.
</P>
<P>
The IPE urged the government to allow fuel sources to compete
on an equitable basis by reforming electricity trading
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that it also asked to abolish the moratorium on the
construction of gas fired generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
In order to keep market stable, the IPE said that the
government should take measures to avoid distorting the market
through artificial support as is being discussed for coal.
</P>
<P>
The IPE also asked the government to consider divesting the
major generators of some of their capacity in order to allow
effective competition to develop.
</P>
<P>
Lynton Jones, Chief Executive of the IPE said, "With the
current OFFER review of trading arrangements, the UK has a unique
opportunity to introduce a truly competitive market in the
generation and supply of electricity."
</P>
<P>
"This could provide a lead to the rest of Europe. This
opportunity must not be wasted and we recommend radical action to
ensure that the needs and rights of consumers are satisfied," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The IPE is Europe's leading energy futures and options
exchange, trading Brent Crude, Gas Oil and Natural Gas products
worth between 1 and 2 billion U.S. dollars every day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
