<HEADLINE> Ethiopia-Eritrea Crisis Causes Concern at OAU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The escalating crisis between
Ethiopia and Eritrea has caused much concern and become one of
the important issues at the current 68th ordinary session of the
Council of Ministers of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
opened here Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim described this
unfortunate development as a severe setback to the effort for
peace, security and stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Since the eruption of the crisis, i have maintained close
contacts with both parties as well as with African leaders whom i
have encouraged to assist in defusing the tension prevailing
between the two countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his discussions with Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
and Eritrean President Isaias Afwerki earlier in Addis Ababa and
Asmara, he added, both leaders were conscious of the far-reaching
and devastating consequences of war and expressed their readiness
to explore all avenues to avoid the use of force.
</P>
<P>
The crisis situation has been deteriorating in the last few
days with reports of border skirmishes involving loss of life and
the situation is extremely grave, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General warned that a military confrontation
could only bring about suffering and destruction to both
countries and peoples.
</P>
<P>
"It is a conflict which no one can win. There can only be
losers. And the losers will not only be Ethiopia and Eritrea or
for that matter the Horn of Africa Region but the continent as a
whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general therefore urged to the leaders of both
countries to exercise maximum restraint, to put an end to the
fighting and explore ways for an early and peaceful solution to
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis between Ethiopia and Eritrea demands
greater determination among OAU member states to act in concert
and requires increased resources to enable the organization to
fulfil its responsibilities, he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
