<HEADLINE> Egypt, Libya Discuss Boosting Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Libya Thursday examined the
current level of their trade exchange and explored ways of
enhancing future cooperation, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaily, after
meeting with Libyan Secretary of Economy and Trade Abdel-Hafez
el-Ziletny here, described Egyptian-Libyan relations as close, but
said that the economic relationship did not measure up to the
political one.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have already signed 11 pacts covering different
domains, including economic integration, investment promotion and
the prevention of double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Libyan trade exchange stood at 145 million
U.S. dollars in 1997, including 70 million dollars of Egyptian
exports to Libya. Gowaily described the volume of two-way trade as
"quite a limited sum considering the capabilities of their
markets."
</P>
<P>
Up to 90 percent of Libya's exports to Egypt are made up of
various types of iron products in addition to petrochemicals,
while Egypt's exports are limited to agricultural and food
products, textiles, medicines and leather products, he said.
</P>
<P>
To infuse more vigor into bilateral relations, Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi had planned to start a visit to Egypt last
Tuesday, but the trip has been postponed indefinitely without
explanation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
