<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Boosts Labor Mobility With Pension Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- European Union social affairs
ministers agreed Thursday on a proposal to safeguard company
pension rights for workers who take jobs in other EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was hailed by European Commission officials as
the first beginning step toward removing the obstacle to free
movement of workers within the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
Under their agreement, workers who move from one EU country to
another will maintain the same pension rights as if they had
switched employers in the original country.
</P>
<P>
"When workers move from one member state to another they are
now going to have their rights preserved in so far as their
contributions to supplementary pensions are concerned," European
Social Affairs Commissioner Padraig Flynn said after the ministers
council meeting in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that complementary pensions are becoming
more important to workers. "They (complementary pensions) are
used much more than in the past in protecting standards of living
for workers," said Flynn.
</P>
<P>
Between 80 and 90 percent of workers employed in the private
sector are members of supplementary pension schemes in the
Netherlands, Denmark and France.
</P>
<P>
Right now, however, people who move from one job to another
across the European Union can expect losing some or even all of
their supplementary pension rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
