<HEADLINE> OAU Hails Reduction of Members' Arrears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General Salim Ahmed
Salim of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) Thursday
described the financial situation of the 53-member body as
"positive and encouraging".
</P>
<P>
"The financial situation of the organization has continued to
improve since the Harare sessions" last year, Salim told the 68th
ordinary session of the OAU council of ministers being held here
in the capital of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The continued determined efforts of member states aimed at
honoring their financial obligations to OAU, particularly at
clearing their arrears, have led to the reduction by almost half
of arrears over the last years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim, who sees the development as a major progress to feed
the pan-African organization, did not give concrete figures to
show the arrears of some member states.
</P>
<P>
A financial report circulated here earlier said OAU is now
owed more than 48 million U.S. Dollars in contribution arrears,
which represents about 150 percent of the continental
organization's current budget of some 31.2 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said 20 of the 53 member states were up to date in
their contributions by May 21 this year, while six countries have
lost their right to speak at the 34th OAU summit opening next
Monday due to accumulated contribution arrears.
</P>
<P>
Under the rules of the organization, ministers and presidents
of countries that default in payments for three to 12 years are
barred from speaking during OAU meetings and prohibited from
presenting candidates for OAU posts.
</P>
<P>
This time, however, the leaders of delegations from defaulting
countries will be requested to speak on issues directly
connected with their respective states, according to sources
here.
</P>
<P>
Another four countries will also be sanctioned unless they pay
all or part of their arrears before the end of the coming summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
