<HEADLINE> Britain Hopes Improved Turkish-EU Ties Helpful for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- British High Commissioner to Cyprus
David Madden said here Thursday that the improved relations
between the European Union (EU) and Turkey would assist efforts
for a political settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides, Madden said the forthcoming EU summit, due to be held
in Britain's Welsh capital Cardiff in mid-June, would offer an
opportunity to the 15 European leaders to discuss EU's
relationship with Turkey and the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that "if the relationship between the EU
and Turkey is put on a marginally better footing, that should be
helpful for our efforts in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Madden refrained from outlining the expectations for the
Cardiff summit with regard to Turkey, but he noted that the
period after the summit would be a "very good occasion to see
what the possibilities are on Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"We will have to think about Cyprus in any case whatever
the outcome of Cardiff is, whatever the Turkish reaction is,
because speaking of Cyprus, the goal remains to work toward a
political settlement," the British diplomat pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the EU would continue its peace efforts on
Cyprus and would not give up.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of the talks with
Cypriot President Clerides in protest against the EU decision to
start accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said that he would not return to the negotiating
table unless his entity in northern Cyprus controlled by the
Turkish Cypriots is recognized and the Cypriot government
suspends the talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Cyprus' purchase of the Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missiles, Madden dismissed suggestions that Britain
opposes the deployment of such missiles because the powerful radar
system accompanying them would be able to track down aircrafts
flying in and out of the two British bases on the island.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the former colonial power, has retained the two
military bases under its sovereign control since it granted Cyprus
independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
The missiles, ordered by the Cypriot government from Russia in
January 1997, are expected to be delivered in mid-August this
year. The deal was opposed by countries including the United
States and Britain, while Turkey has threatened to strike the
missiles if they are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third in the aftermath of a pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
</TEXT>
