<HEADLINE> Indonesia Reaches Rescheduling Deal with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Frankfurt, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and 13 foreign banks
have reached a debt rescheduling agreement involving dozens of
billions of U.S. dollars in credit owed by the country's banking
sector and private companies, negotiators said in Frankfurt
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed Thursday after four days of
negotiations at the Frankfurt headquarters of Germany's largest
commercial bank -- Deutsche Bank, Indonesian banks would be
offered an extension of up to four years in the repayment of 9.2
billion U.S. dollars of short-term debts due by the end of March,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The deal also foresees the creation of a rescheduling agency to
help Indonesia's private companies to get a grip on their foreign
debts which are estimated at about 60 billion dollars, said the
Deutsche Bank, which coordinated the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
These companies would be offered an eight-year extension in the
repayment of their liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the foreign banks also offered to help Indonesia in
financing its foreign trade. The repayment of Jarkata's trade
credit of between four to six billion dollars would be extended by
one year.  
</P>
