<HEADLINE> P5 Foreign Ministers Determined to Resolve Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the five
permanent members of the Security Council (P5) vowed to pursue
efforts to resolve disputes between India and Pakistan including
Kashmir in a joint communique issued at the end of their one-day
meeting here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from China, France, Russia, the United
Kingdom and the United States held closed-door talks to coordinate
their response to the grave situation created by the nuclear tests
carried out last month by India and then by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers pledged that they will actively encourage India
and Pakistan to find mutually acceptable solutions, through direct
dialogue, that address the root causes of the tension, including
Kashmir, and to try to build confidence rather than seek
confrontation," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
They also urged both parties to avoid threatening military
movements, cross-border violations, or other provocative acts.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers affirm their readiness to assist India and
Pakistan, in a manner acceptable to both sides, in promoting
reconciliation and cooperation," it said.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the P5 could take actions
"individually or collectively" to foster peace and security in
South Asia. The possible actions include:
</P>
<P>
- To encourage India and Pakistan to adopt practical measures
to prevent an arms race;
</P>
<P>
- To prevent the export of equipment, materials or technology
that could in any way assist programs in India or Pakistan for
nuclear weapons or for ballistic missiles capable of delivering
such weapons;
</P>
<P>
- To do all they could to facilitate a reduction of tensions
between those states, and to provide assistance, at the request of
both parties, in the development and implementation of confidence-
and security-building measures.
</P>
<P>
The ministers pledged to work actively to build broad support
in the international community for the objectives they agreed
Thursday at the Geneva meeting, which are to strengthen peace and
stability in South Asia, to encourage restraint by India and
Pakistan, to promote the resolution of outstanding differences,
and to bolster the international non-proliferation regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
