<HEADLINE> Egypt Calls For Wider Efforts to Save Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Thursday called for greater
involvement of the international community in saving the faltering
Mideast peace process as the prospect for an Arab summit seemed
diminishing.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, political advisor to President Hosni Mubarak,
issued the appeal after meeting here with Arab league Secretary
General Esmat Abdel Meguid.
</P>
<P>
"We want a European involvement and we want an expansion of the
circle of international support to the Arab position," he
said. "We are interested in the European Union, Russia, China and
countries that actively participated in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian official said Arab countries do not intend to
oppose coordination with Washington in pushing forward the peace
process, which has been stalled for over one year due to Israel's
hardline policies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly asked for a delay in holding the summit
in order to allow it more time to convince Israel to buy its
proposal on a 13.1 percent troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Baz said the Arab leaders would meet after the fate of the
American initiative is determined to "define what to ask from the
United States."
</P>
<P>
In the past weeks, there have been intensive consultations on
whether and how an Arab summit should be held to work out a common
strategy to confront Israel's intransigent policies.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has been traveling around the
region lobbying for support. However, differences over how to deal
with Israel prevented Arab countries from reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Syria, for example, wants a hardline Arab stance while Egypt
and Jordan, who signed peace with Israel, embrace more moderate
tones.
</P>
<P>
But Baz said the differences did not preclude a common Arab
stand. Cairo, Syrian capital Damascus and Saudi capital Riyadh
have been named as possible venues for the proposed summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
