<HEADLINE> Annan in Effort to Find Solution to East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is committed to finding a solution to the question of East
Timor, his spokesman said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed in his recent letter to President B.J.
Habibie of Indonesia, the spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General assured the President of his commitment
to work with Indonesia and Portugal "to find, as early as
possible, a just, comprehensive and internationally acceptable
solution" to the question, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Annan held an internal meeting with his aides on Tuesday to
review the progress of his good offices on the question and to
consider further steps to advance the negotiations under his
auspices, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Under a United Nations resolution adopted in 1960, East Timor
with an area of 14,874 square kilometers and a population of
750,000 is a territory administered by Portugal.
</P>
<P>
In 1975, self-rule of East Timor was declared by Portugal by a
referendum. That was followed by the entrance of Indonesian troops
into the Island the same year.  
