<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angolan Peace Process Again in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Yin Yongjian)
</P>
<P>
LUANDA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The long lasting Angolan peace
process is now once again in crisis with no progress made in the
past two months due to the obstruction of the opposition National
Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
According to the new agenda passed by the the government and
UNITA on March 6, the peace process is due to conclude at the end
of March. However, since efforts were thwarted in establishing
national authority in the four "sensitive" regions of Bailundo,
Andulo, where the UNITA headquarters are located, and Nharea and
Mungo, the peace process is stopped.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, U.N. special envoy to Angola and a major
mediator in the peace process, then initiated a program to rid of
the crisis, stipulating that the Angolan government cease its
anti-UNITA propaganda, that it should not issue any news
concerning UNITA's army mobilization and sabotage without the
confirmation of the United Nations observers mission.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it ruled that UNITA must hand over the
above-mentioned four regions by May 31. However, UNITA violated
the rule with the excuse of insecurity and postpone the deadline
to the end of June, which met with strong opposition from the
Angolan government and observer countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite UNITA's announcement in early March that it had
demilitarized completely, evidence shows it still keeps army
units which were responsible for many armed attacks around the
country.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday the organization "doctors without frontiers" were
attacked in central Angola. In the 273 UNITA-occupied regions
where local authority was resumed, at least 40 have been snatched
back by the UNITA, including five cities.
</P>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, Angolan government spokesman in the joint
committee of the peace process, said Wednesday that if the UNITA
continues to obstruct the development of the peace process, the
government will take up measures which include the closure of
UNITA headquarters in Luanda, and decide whether UNITA MPs will
remain in the national assembly or whether its officials will
remain in the national unity and reconciliation government.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman admitted that his government might suspend the
joint committee of peace process unilaterally on the pretext that
UNITA failed to implement the Lusaka peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the current stalemate is mainly a
result of lack of mutual trust, especially on the part of UNITA.
Under the peace accord, UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi must come to
the capital Luanda, but he refused to do so citing no guarantee
of personal safety. He is now living either in Bailundo or
Andulo, the handover of which will render him "homeless."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council will discuss the peace process in
Angola Friday. Beye has already left for New York to attend the
meeting. Analysts here believe that the Security Council meeting
might come up with a resolution to impose a third batch of
sanctions on the former rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
Although the peace process has been stalled, observers noted
that the difficulty is only temporary, for neither side wishes to
open fire once again. With the mediation of and pressure from
the international community, peace will become reality in the
end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
