<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Women to Play Role in Conflict Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The role of African women in
conflict prevention and resolution was underlined at the current
68th ordinary session of the council of ministers of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) opened here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim, the
African Women's Committee on Peace and Development will serve as
an advisory body on issues relating to gender and the involvement
of women in the mainstream of the continent's efforts aimed at
preventing, managing and resolving conflicts and their active
participation in decision making for sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The committee was established at the 40th anniversary of the
U.N. Economic Commission of Africa (UNECA) in pursuance to a
decision of the OAU council of ministers earlier this year as
part of the effort to strengthen OAU's capacity to deal with
conflict situations in Africa.
</P>
<P>
African women can and should make contribution to the
promotion of peace and development, the OAU chief said at the
council session Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Salim expressed regret at the rather modest contribution by
member states so far to the OAU peace fund for sustaining the
activities of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention,
Management and Resolution and urged the council of ministers to
extend support and encouragement to the on-going process aimed at
enhancing the efficiency and efficacy of the OAU mechanism.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, African women have shown strong will and
enthusiasm for peace and development in the continent. As early
as in May, 1996, the African first ladies had expressed their
support to the cause of their husbands for peace and development
at the African First Ladies' summit in Abuja, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
