<HEADLINE> U.S. Needs Further Cut Air Power in Gulf: General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Air Force general
Thursday called for additional reduction of air power in the Gulf
to a level at which the the U.S. forces were deployed in the
region before last November.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to see the size of that force reduced to a level
that we can sustain on an indefinite basis without undue stress
and strain on the force," Gen. Richard Hawley, chief of the Air
Combat Command, told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The United States recently began cutting its military presence
in the Gulf to some 200 warplanes and one aircraft carrier, a
level reached last November before a major build-up in a face-off
with Baghdad over U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
But Hawley said operational stress was mounting in the
shrinking Air Force because of growing deployments to world
trouble spots, and he said deeper cuts could be made in the Gulf
for now. He advocated a reduction to pre-November Air Force
deployment level in Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and elsewhere in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. Air Force had proved its ability to get
aircraft to the Gulf from American bases within 48 hours if
necessary. So "we don't have to have our forces deployed on a
continuous basis in forward areas," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
