<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Accepts Peace Proposal by U.S, Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi announces Thursday evening that his government fully
accepts the proposal presented by the United States and Rwanda
for peaceful resolution of the Ethio-Eritrean border crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meles made the announcement while addressing the nation at a
press conference held at the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "Since the proposal of the
facilitators is consistent with the Ethiopian position, the
Ethiopian government fully accepts the proposal of the
facilitators in the belief that the proposal would lay a firm
foundation for the peaceful resolution of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
The proposal presented by the representatives of the two
countries suggests that the Eritrean government withdraw its
troops from Badme under the supervision of an observer force.
</P>
<P>
Their proposals also demands the reinstatement of the
Ethiopian administration that existed in the Badme area prior to
the clash.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Meles urged the Defense Forces of Ethiopia to "take
all necessary measures against the repeated aggressions of the
Eritrean government and to safeguard the territorial integrity of
the country."
</P>
<P>
He called upon Ethiopian people "to take all the actions
necessary for the safeguarding of thir country according to
directives to be issued by organs of the government and the
defense forces of ethiopia."
</P>
<P>
Meles said, "Although the Ethiopian government maintains its
stand for peace and supports the compromise proposal presented by
the governments of the United States and Rwanda even now, the
continued aggression of the Eritrean government has exhausted
our patience."  
</P>
</TEXT>
