<HEADLINE> WHO to Help Tanzania Reduce Maternal Death Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO), in collaboration with the Tanzanian Ministry of
Health, will later this month start a 10-year program with
emphasis on reducing maternal death rate.
</P>
<P>
An official with the WHO office in Dar es Salaam said Thursday
that the program will help district health centers to play a better
role in dealing with reproductive health problems.
</P>
<P>
The WHO official, who preferred anonymity, said maternal death
rate during childbirth in Tanzania and in many other African
countries has been high. In Tanzania, one in 18 women risks
maternal death.
</P>
<P>
He said the strategies for the program include preventing
abortion complications and reproductive tract infections
especially sexually transmitted diseases including HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
WHO will also be involved in the control of female genital
mutilation and other reproductive health problems, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
