<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank Denies Wrongdoings in Nazi Gold Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Deutsche Bank Thursday
denied charges that it had played a role in helping trade the
gold robbed from Holocaust victims during the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
The bank's remarks were made in reaction to a collective
lawsuit brought by Holocaust survivors in New York Wednesday which
reportedly claimed that the Deutsche Bank and another big German
bank -- Dresdner Bank -- had profited from personal assets like
gold teeth fillings, gold jewelry and coins seized by German
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
The Holocaust survivors also demanded 18 billion U.S. dollars
in compensations from the two biggest German banks.
</P>
<P>
The Deutsche Bank, however, said that an independent research
conducted by a British historian had showed that the gold received
by the Deutsche Bank from Nazi Germany's central bank had been
delivered in the form of bullions so that its origin was not
known.
</P>
<P>
Both the Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank stressed Thursday that
they could not comment more specifically until they had seen the
lawsuit filed in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
