awarded China's Engineering Science and Technology Award and Tah
Kah Kee Science Prize here today.
</P>
<P>
The two prizes, highly appraised by academicians of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS) and the Chinese Academy of Engineering
(CAE), represent the highest kudos for China's scientists.
</P>
<P>
Shao Xianghua, a metallurgy expert, said in a speech that
although China is the top iron and steel producer in the world,
its per capita output, technological level and economic index are
all relatively backward in international terms.
</P>
<P>
The 85-year-old scientist said that he intends to make more
contributions to China's metallurgical industry in the time left
to him and do his best to help foster a new generation of
scientists for the country.
</P>
<P>
The 22 prize winners are engaged in various fields, including
architecture, agriculture, medical science and electronics.
</P>
