<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One of Cyprus' Oldest Newspapers to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- One of Cyprus' oldest newspapers,
"Agon" (Struggle) will close down in fierce industrial competition
after 34 years of circulation.
</P>
<P>
"Agon" (Struggle), the Cyprus' only tabloid-style daily will
shut its door from next Monday, TV and radio stations reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Facing stiff competition from TV and radio as well as other
papers, the money-strapped newspaper was unable to pay the staff
for the past few months, said chief editor of the paper Panayiotis
Papademetris.
</P>
<P>
"Agon" was founded in 1964, four years after the island's
independence, by the current Justice Minister Nicos Koshis.
</P>
<P>
It was initially a magazine before it became a weekly
newspaper and a daily later.
</P>
<P>
Its circulation slumped from 4,500-5,500 a day to 2,500
following a rise in price last year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Friday, the Journalists Union of
Cyprus called for measures by the government and other interested
parties to protect publication of newspapers on the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
