<HEADLINE> Hang Seng Bank Scholarships Support Chinese Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Hang Seng Bank will, for the
second year, award scholarships to outstanding students both in
China's mainland and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR), to study at Harvard and Princeton universities, the bank
announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
As the recipients of the scheme's Hong Kong program, Lam
Wai-chung of Diocesan Girls' School and Kueh Hao-yuan of Diocesan
Boy's School will undertake undergraduate studies in economics at
Harvard and biology and chemistry at Princeton respectively from
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Selection of the other scholarship recipients under the
mainland program is under way by China's Ministry of Education,
which manages the program on behalf of Hang Seng Bank. They will
take up post-graduate studies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Under the bank's overseas scholarship scheme, the scholarships
go to students featuring excellent scholastic achievements, strong
leadership abilities and a keen commitment to China's mainland and
the Hong Kong SAR. After completing their overseas studies, the
Hong Kong SAR recipients are required to return for employment for
a minimum period of three years and the mainland recipients must
go back to the mainland for employment for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
The scholarships cover all tuition fees, textbooks, reasonable
living expenses including board and lodging and one round-trip air
ticket to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1933 as a principal member of the HSBC Group, Hang
Seng Bank is the second largest locally-incorporated bank in Hong
Kong. It has 146 branches in the Hong Kong SAR and two branches
and two representative offices in China's mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
