<HEADLINE> 1st Group of China's Senior Members of Both CAS and CAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Eleven veteran scientists enjoying
high prestige and commanding universal respect were granted the
title of "senior member" of both the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS) and the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) here today:
</P>
<P>
Qian Xuesen, born in 1911, "father of China's guided missiles",
contributed significantly to China's strategic guided missile,
satellite launching and systems engineering research.
</P>
<P>
Yan Kai, born in 1912, is an expert in hydraulic engineering,
and has participated in the planning of many big dam projects,
including the Three Gorges Dam.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guangdou, born in 1912, was one of the pioneers of
China's hydraulic and hydropower engineering work. He directed the
research into a series of key problems in the construction of many
hydropower stations on China's major rivers.
</P>
<P>
Yan Dongsheng, born in 1918, played a leading role in
China's research into and development of new materials.
</P>
<P>
Hou Xianglin, born in 1912, developed new lubricating materials
for China's nuclear weapons and guided missiles. His research into
chemical industry and oil refining helped China to make its own
aviation fuel.
</P>
<P>
Wang Daheng, born in 1915, was the developer of China first
laser instrument, making great contributions to China's optical
research.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jieping, born in 1917, is one of the leading scientists in
urological surgery in China. He developed a male sterilization
technique.
</P>
<P>
Luo Peilin, born in 1913, played an important role in laying
the foundation for the production of electronic components in
China. He directed the development of China's first long-distance
radar system.
</P>
<P>
Li Guohao, born in 1913, participated in the design of the
Yangtze River Bridge. He is world-renowned for his theory on
suspended bridges.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wei, born in 1913, has made great contributions to both
the theory and application of mechanics. He was the supervisor of
China's first doctorate student in engineering.
</P>
<P>
Shao Xianghua, born in 1913, was one of the pioneers of China's
steel industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
