Japan overcame a slow start and did not take over 24-23 until
9:47 into the game on Takako Kato's basket. Then Japan never
trailed and led the first half 60-43.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese, which enlarged the gap as many as 28 points
before Hungary's last goal at last seconds, outscored the
Hungarians 54 percent to 46 and hit in 11 three-pointers, compared
with their opponents' three.
</P>
<P>
Andrea Karolyi led Hungary on the scoreboard with 20 points,
followed by Dora Kalmar-Nagy's 17.
</P>
<P>
Hungary was fourth in the European championship last year but
disqualified for the last world champioship. 
