<HEADLINE> Samaranch Pushes for Change in Olympic Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch said on
Friday that he will urge the next FIFA president to release all
best soccer players for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The head of the International Olympic Committee said that the
current under-23 format for Olympic soccer should be dropped to
open up the Olympics to all the world's best players.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said he will discuss the matter with the winner of
next Monday's FIFA presidential election in Paris between Lennart
Johansson, head of the European federation UEFA, and FIFA
secretary general Sepp Blatter.
</P>
<P>
"This is something we have in our agenda to discuss with the
new president the possibility to increase the number of players
without the age limit," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
FIFA, eager to guard the supremacy of its World Cup, has
restricted the Olympic soccer competition to players under the age
of 23, resulting in an influx of amateurs for the Olympic soccer
tournament.
</P>
<P>
However, the restriction was relaxed for the 1996 Atlanta Games
and the 2000 Sydney Games to allow teams to field three players
over 23. 
</P>
