<HEADLINE> Mugabe to Leave for OAU Summit Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe,
outgoing chairman of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
will leave here Sunday for Ouagadougou, capital of Burkina Faso,
to attend 34th OAU summit scheduled Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit, set to emphasize the need to seek
African solutions to African problems, will center on the themes
of peace, security and stability as well as economic cooperation
and integration.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Foreign Ministry said in a statement Friday it
was the contention of the OAU that Africa should lead and
increase its role in its security.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, the OAU, while affirming that the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and
security rests with the United Nations, upholds that under
certain exceptional circumstances the organization could
undertake deployment for observation missions," the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
On economic issues, the OAU leaders were expected to look at
the heightened need for better transport, communications and
information technology sectors in view of the adoption of the
treaty establishing the African Economic Community, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who will hand over the OAU chairmanship to Blaise
Campaore, president of Burkina Faso, is expected to address the
summit mainly on issues of conflict management and resolution.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan Mudenge is already in
Ouagadougou where he is attending the council of ministers
meeting preparing an agenda for the OAU heads of state and
government assembly. 
</P>
