<HEADLINE> Veteran Scientists Embrace New CAS System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- "China should give top priority to
training young talented people, to bring their potential into full
play by letting them do pioneering research," said Guo Lingzhi, an
academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The 83-year-old structural geologist became a senior CAS
members today, along with 163 other academicians over 80 years old.
</P>
<P>
"Introducing the senior member system into CAS is very
encouraging for young talented people, who should be the backbones
of CAS," said Guo, who now teaches Ph.D students at Nanjing
University.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent State Council decision, CAS and the
Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) will adopt the senior
membership system as of July 1 this year. Under the system,
academicians of CAS and CAE will become senior members once they
turn 80 years old.
</P>
<P>
The senior members can participate in consultation activities
but should no longer stay in the leadership or take part in
nominating or electing new CAS and CAE members.
</P>
<P>
"I'm old and would rather devote my limited time and energy to
teaching," said Wang Zhizhuo, a specialist in remote
sensing technology and topography. "I'm proud that many of my
students have joined CAS."
</P>
<P>
At the advanced age of 89, Wang still reads in the library
every day. "My eyesight is failing, and I am no longer as
conversant with new software as my students are," he said.
</P>
<P>
Most former academicians expressed their willingness to embrace
the senior membership system, which has been described by CAS
officials as "good for the health of old scientists."
</P>
<P>
Each of the senior members will get an annual stipend of 10,000
yuan (about 1,200 US dollars), while they still receive their full
salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
