<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Memorial Sirens Wail in Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- All the 150 air-raid stations in
this biggest city in soutwest China sounded their sirens today to
commemorate the thousands of people killed in Japanese air attacks
57 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On June 5, 1941, a group of 24 Japanese aircraft bombed the
city, then temporary capital of the nation. Nearly 3,000 local
people died during the five-hour raid.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that the Japanese invaders bombed the
city from the air many times, causing more than 10,000 deaths and
22,000 serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
It was the worst air raid in China during the Anti-Japanese War
(1937-1945).
</P>
<P>
A "Chongqing Bombings Sculpture Wall" in memory of the
incident is to be built by the city government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
