<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Backs EU Computer Networking Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization's
(WTO) appeals tribunal overturned on Friday an original WTO
verdict against the European Union (EU) involving its row with the
United States over computer equipment classification.
</P>
<P>
The new verdict holds that the EU was in compliance with its
obligations under world trade rules.
</P>
<P>
The case, filed by the United States, involved 425 million ecus
(381 million U.S. dollars) worth of U.S. local area network (LAN)
equipment exports to EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Disputes about the case arose in 1996 when the United States
filed a WTO complaint against the EU, alleging that Brussels had
violated WTO commitments by reclassifying LAN equipment into a
higher tariff category.
</P>
<P>
The United States holds that the LAN equipment should be in the
Automatic Data Processor (ADP) category, with a lower tariff duty.
</P>
<P>
The American side claimed that Britain and Ireland, two EU
members, had previously placed LAN equipment in a lower tariff
category, but in 1995 the equipment was placed in the higher
category throughout the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
Ireland and Britain raised tariffs on LAN networking equipment
from 4.9 percent to 7.5 percent after the EU adopted a regulation
in 1995 classifying the networking equipment as telecommunications
equipment, which carries a higher tariff duty.
</P>
<P>
The EU appealed to the WTO after the organization brought down
a verdict in favor of the U.S. complaint against Brussels, in
February.
</P>
<P>
The EU has said that LAN equipment should be classed as telecom
apparatus rather than as ADPs because its main function is to
transmit and communicate data.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government itself had also classified LAN products as
telecom apparatus at the time of the Uruguay Round of trade
negotiations which ended formally in 1994, said the EU.
</P>
<P>
Under the global Information Technology Agreement, however,
tariffs on LAN equipment will be abolished by the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0083 </DOCNO>
