<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volunteers Work for Yangtze River Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 50,000 young volunteers today
went onto the streets of this capital of central China's Hubei
Province to distribute leaflets promoting protection of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The volunteers, from the Yangtze River Water Conservancy
Committee and Yangtze Navigation Administration Bureau, also took
to boats to clean waste from the river.
</P>
<P>
The two activities are part of a national effort to mark
International Environment Day, which fell today.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze, which runs through Hubei and another 10 provinces
and municipalities, is China's longest river, more than 6,300 km
long. It has one trillion cu m of water resources.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River valley, which has a population of more than
400 million, is one of the most economically developed areas in
China. But as economic activities increase, the river has been
threatened by worsening pollution.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicate that 15 billion tons of liquid sewage
is discharged in the river each year, about half of the national
total. Vessels on the river produce an average of more than 300
million tons of liquid waste each year.
</P>
<P>
Though the overall water quality is good, 22.4 percent of the
Yangtze river water has been polluted, an official source said.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the worsening pollution, the Chinese government has
invested a large amount of funds in afforestation and water
conservancy projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
