Two more bodies were found among the last wreckage of the
crashed train removed by rescue workers from debris early Friday
morning. Another body has also been recovered later this morning,
bringing the death total to 96.
</P>
<P>
The InterCity Express (ICE), Germany's fastest train, derailed
at 11:10 Wednesday morning and slammed into a road bridge near
Eschede, bringing hundreds of tons of concrete to crash down onto
the middle section of the train.
</P>
<P>
With two days passed, a broken wheel is now being treated as
the most likely cause for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Bonn on Friday, a Transport
Ministry spokesman, Veit Steinle, confirmed that investigators had
found a damaged wheel ring on the first carriage of train. The
ring is said to be the essential part to hold the wheel onto the
rail track.
</P>
<P>
"It cannot be ruled out that the broken wheel has played a role
in the derailment," Steinle said.
</P>
<P>
Wheel parts that had been found Thursday about six kilometers
from the crash site indicated that a wheel might have broken
there, leading to the derailment afterwards, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he also stressed that all other possible causes were
being investigated at the moment.
</P>
<P>
As a precaution, the German rail authorities Thursday pulled 60
ICE trains out of service to undergo mechanical checks. With no
technical defect found, 10 of them already went back into service
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Germany has now 104 ICE trains in operation. Those withdrawn
were the first-generation expresses in service since 1991. The
crashed train also belongs to this rank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
