<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FILMART '98 Expected to Help Open New Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Participants of the coming Hong
Kong International Film Market (FILMART '98) are keen to open new
markets for their productions, especially in China's mainland,
Alan Wong, director of services of the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC), said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the TDC, FILMART '98 set for June 24-26 this year
has attracted more than 50 international film and TV firms. Open
to trade visitors only, the event will offer a wide range of new
products from movies and TV programs to VCD/DVD production
technology.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's film industry is experiencing a difficult time,
especially after the Asian financial crisis. FILMART will serve as
a paramount platform for industry players to exchange information,
helping them catch up with the latest market situation in Asia and
to look for new business opportunities," Wong said at a press
preview here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the Asian economic turmoil, we are still optimistic
about the market potential for film and TV production within the
region. The boom in Asian cable and satellite channels over the
last few years has created many opportunities for producers and
buyers to explore," he said.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural event last year proved to be very successful,
Wong said. Both exhibitors and buyers agreed that it strengthened
Hong Kong's lead as an international distribution hub and a right
place to do film and TV business in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The event's target has been expanded this year to include TV
and video buyers, particularly those from China's mainland. More
than 120 buyers from the mainland would participate in the
three-day event.
</P>
<P>
As the TV sector of China's mainland is expanding rapidly,
which provides a market with immense potential, FILMART '98 could
introduce new products to buyers from there, said Woody Tsung,
chief executive of the Hong Kong, Kowloon &AMP; New Territories Motion
Picture Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economic slowdown is a reality to face, admitted
Raymond Wong, chairman of the Movie Producers and Distributors
Association of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"A decline in attendance for local films, coupled with the
Asian economic downturn, has prompted our producers to rethink our
strategies," he said. The only way out would be to find new
markets for their products and to produce a wider variety of films
to meet varied tastes of the audience, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
A series of seminars will be held during FILMART '98 and video
screening booths will be introduced to enable buyers to view a
variety of titles with minimal distraction, according to the
organizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
