<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Issues Regulations on Mini-Buses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will standardize the
management of mini-bus companies and their service with a specific
regulations that will go into effect on August 1.
</P>
<P>
The third meeting of the Standing Committee of the Eleventh
Municipal People's Congress today approved new administrative
regulations on the city's mini-buses.
</P>
<P>
Mini-buses, with eight to 19 passenger seats, often have
regular routes. They can be hailed anywhere on their routes.
</P>
<P>
These buses are considered a useful supplement to large
commuter buses and taxis, said Fu Bonan, chief of the Municipal
Administrative Commission.
</P>
<P>
Beijing had only 25 mini-buses in 1984. By 1997, however, the
city had about 4,100, employing 9,000 people. The municipal
government made 16 million yuan (about 1.93 million U.S. dollars)
in taxes collected from them in that year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, mini-buses transported more than 190 million
passengers on their 340 regular routes, the transportation
capacity accounting for 4.4 percent of the total passenger
transportation capacity of the city.
</P>
<P>
Complaints about mini-buses include lack of hygiene, dangerous
driving and overcharging.
</P>
<P>
The new 31-article regulations cover all these points of
contention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
