<HEADLINE> Zambia to Upgrade Health Centers Countrywide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is to
upgrade about 400 health centers throughout the country,
especially in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Ben Chirwa, spokesman of Zambia's Central Board of Health,
disclosed Thursday that the board would improve the conditions of
service for all its health workers, Zambia Daily Mail reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We will give them better salaries, introduce rural
allowances, cater for housing and many more to encourage the
health workers operate in any area of Zambia," said Chirwa.
</P>
<P>
He noted that unlike in urban areas where medical personnel
will have to cater for their own transport and accommodation, the
rural staff will be given these facilities as incentives.
</P>
<P>
Chirwa added that staff will be sent to different rural health
centers immediately after a report to ascertain the needs of
personnel in these areas.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the rural areas are also critical
in the country's health system and therefore all the issues
concerned should be tackled seriously.
</P>
<P>
About 55 percent Zambians live in the rural areas where most
of the people are suffering from insufficient health care and
health personnel prefer to work in cities rather than in the poor
countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
