<HEADLINE> Paris Court Rejects Euro Request on World Cup Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Tribunal of Grand Instance of
Paris Friday declared unacceptable a request by 30 deputies of the
European Parliament who disputed the way of distribution of
tickets of World Cup matches by France.
</P>
<P>
These deputies said that 2.5 million tickets distributed by the
French Committee of Organization of World Cup (CFO), the
International Federation of Football (FIFA) and the French
Federation of Football (FFF) are discriminatory because most of
them are reserved for French fans.
</P>
<P>
The deputies, who are from Belgium, Britain, the Netherlands,
Germany, Greece, Austria, Italy and Denmark, said that the
remaining 712,484 tickets be distributed to anyone who wishes to
watch the matches whatever his nationality.
</P>
<P>
They also said that the CFO, FIFA and FFF be condemned and
forced to pay 100,000 francs (16,666 U.S. dollars) for damage of
interests.
</P>
<P>
The court said that their request is not justified because they
themselves have not applied for the tickets, and therefore they
cannot take legal action in the interests of others or the general
public. 
</P>
