<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Concrete Steps to Curb Securities Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China's two stock exchanges -- in
Shanghai and Shenzhen -- publicized the revisions to their
respective securities trading rules today, with the aim of
checking reckless speculation more effectively.
</P>
<P>
The revised provisions clearly define the abnormal fluctuations
of stock prices based on their fluctuation range and turnover,
making it easier for the stock exchanges to make judgments and
suspend the trading of stocks showing abnormal performances.
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts said that the new provisions will be conducive
to curbing over-speculation on the stock market and protecting the
interests of individual investors through increasing the
transparency of the market.
</P>
<P>
China's securities market now boasts more than 800 listed
companies with a total capitalization of 2.08 trillion yuan at the
end of April.
</P>
<P>
But the volatility of some stock prices as a result of
excessive speculation remains a serious problem. Some
institutional and big investors manipulate the prices of some
stocks, which poses a serious threat to the standardization and
stability of the market.
</P>
<P>
The revised trading regulations should prevent such practices
by increasing the information transparency of stock market.
</P>
<P>
"Transparency, fairness and justice are the soul of the
securities market," said an official with the China Securities
Regulatory Commission, adding that the revised regulations will
better help the market supervisors with their clearer definitions
and measurements of "abnormal fluctuations" of stock prices.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese authorities give top priority to the
standardization of the securities market. As an indication, they
are working hard on the long-awaited Securities Law to better
manage the still-immature stock market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Import Maize This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe needs to import at least
600,000 tons of maize to cover a deficit of 300,000 tons and a
similar quantity to replenish the strategic grain reserve (SGR).
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe this year produced only 1.5 million tons of maize,
well below the national consumption requirements of 1.8 million
tons, the Herald daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the Grain Marketing Board (GMB) Martin
Muchero was quoted as saying that Zimbabwe would in real terms
have to import a total of 600,000 tons of maize, including the
300,000 tons needed to boost the SGR.
</P>
<P>
"We have made recommendations to the government to import in
the wake of a shortage we have on the market and we are still
waiting for it to come back to us," he said.
</P>
<P>
The call by the GMB to import maize directly contradicts
statements made by Minister of Lands and Agriculture Kumbirai
Kangai in February this year that Zimbabwe would not import any
maize this year because the SGR had sufficient maize in stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
