<HEADLINE> Soeharto Foundations May Shift Assets to State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's three foundations
chaired by former President Soeharto will consider transferring
their assets to the state at the government's request, one of the
foundations' leaders said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"If the government requests them (assets), we will consider the
request," Dharmais charity foundation deputy chief Sudharmono told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The foundations -- Supersemar, Dharmais and Dakab -- were set
up by Soeharto in 1974 to provide scholarships to students from
the lower-income group and help orphanages and cataract sufferers.
They now have assets totaling 2.4 trillion rupiah (about 240
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Each of the foundations has huge funds. But they are
meaningless to the government. Should the government confiscate
them? I don't think so," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sudharmono said he met with Soeharto on May 29 to discuss
issues concerning the three foundations following Soeharto's
resignation on May 21.
</P>
<P>
In response to calls for investigation in possible fraud,
corruption and collusion in the management of these foundations,
he said the foundations are open to foreign auditors.
</P>
<P>
"But we have to think about the high cost of inviting foreign
auditors," he said, adding that these foundations are audited by
local auditors every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
