<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules Protect Beijing's Ancient Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- New regulations on the protection
of ancient and rare trees were approved here today at a meeting of
the Standing Committee of the Beijing Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, scheduled to go into effect August 1, will
offer protection to 40,852 ancient and rare trees in the Chinese
capital.
</P>
<P>
Trees over 100 years old are regarded as ancient trees.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 6,213 trees more than 300 years old in
the city are unique to China.
</P>
<P>
As many of the ancient trees are found in places of
historic interest, like the Palace Museum, the Summer Palace and
the Temple of Heaven, they are also called living historical
relics.
</P>
<P>
The regulations ban seven kinds of damage to these trees,
including carving on their bark, driving nails into them, breaking
off their branches and cutting them down.
</P>
<P>
When an ancient tree dies, the fact must be reported to the
department in charge, the regulations stipulates. It also affirms
the previous measures taken by the Beijing municipal government to
protect ancient trees, such as establishing files and putting
explanatory labels on them.
</P>
<P>
Construction projects must avoid ancient trees, and if it is
necessary to transplant an ancient tree, permission must be
obtained beforehand from the municipal government, according to
the regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
