<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Regrets Indian Refusal of Mediation Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Friday regretted that
India has rejected the offers of mediation from the U.N. secretary
general as well as Japan, Iran and Bangladesh to promote durable
peace and security in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan supports the resumption of the bilateral talks with
India at the foreign secretary level on the basis of the agreement
reached in Islamabad last June," a Foreign Office spokesman said
in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
"But it is evident now that the bilateral dialogue needs to be
implemented by a broader multilateral process to promote durable
peace and security in South Asia," the spokesman said. "It is
regrettable that India has rejected the offers of mediation from
the U.N. secretary general as well as Japan, Iran, Bangladesh and
others."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the meeting of foreign ministers of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council held Thursday in
Geneva "reflects a recognition of the urgency for the world
community to address the security crisis in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
"We note with satisfaction that the meeting has adopted a
comprehensive approach to peace and security in South Asia and
addressed not only the non-proliferation issue but also the threat
to peace and security, including the need for a solution of the
core issue of Jammu and Kashmir," he said.
</P>
<P>
The five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council are
Britain, China, France, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that the initiative taken by the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council to focus on the
tension and its root-cause in South Asia -- the core issue of
Jammu and Kashmir -- "should be seen as the beginning of a process
of active and continued involvement of the international
community."
</P>
<P>
"This process should be vigorously pursued until a just
settlement of the Kashmir issue is reached and culminated in a
Non-Aggression Pact between Pakistan and India," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
