<HEADLINE> OAU Ministers Call for Restraint from Ethiopia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The border dispute between
Ethiopia and Eritrea has become one of the issues of deep concern
for African countries whose leaders are to gather here to plan
the future of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the Central Organ of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), who held an urgent session Thursday
night, urged both states to exercise restraint so as to achieve a
peaceful settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
A press release circulated here Friday said the ministers
welcomed the efforts of the facilitators of the United States and
Rwanda and urged them to continue with their efforts, while
calling upon both parties to cooperate with the facilitators.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, who are here to attend the on-going 68th
ordinary session of the OAU Council of Ministers, also urged the
two parties to accept a solution that comes through peaceful
means, including adjudication, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged OAU's good offices to the two parties and
the facilitators in the search for a peaceful solution of the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the four-hour urgent meeting on Thursday
midnight, the ministers decided to remain actively seized of the
issue, which has led to high tension particularly with the recent
deployment of troops along the borders.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Council of Ministers session, scheduled to close
Saturday, is to make preparations for the forthcoming OAU summit
starting next Monday.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful solution to the crisis between Ethiopia and Eritrea
is expected to come out at the pending OAU summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
