<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Landslide Victory For Political Realignment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The landslide victory by South Korean
ruling parties in Thursday's local elections is expected to
accelerate President Kim Dae-jung's drive for political
realignment aimed at controlling the National Assembly --
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition of the National Congress for New Politics
(NCNP) and the United Liberal Democrats (ULD) dealt a heavy blow
to the opposition Grand National Party (GNP) by winning 10 of 16
electoral districts in the local elections.
</P>
<P>
The elections, which were held three months after President Kim
took office on February 25, were regarded as a reward for Kim. He
has been fighting against the worst economic crisis in the
country's history, and the GNP, the majority opposition in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The GNP, which now has 149 seats of the 292-member parliament,
refused last March to approve President Kim's nomination of Kim
Jong-pil as prime minister of the country. Kim Jong-pil now serves
as acting prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Following the GNP's disapproval of Kim Jong-pil as cabinet
head, President Kim has repeatedly accused the GNP of failing to
cooperate with his government to overcome the continuing financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, the ruling camp sought a massive political
realignment aimed at taking over parliamentary control from the
GNP.
</P>
<P>
To date, it has successfully lured 11 GNP parliamentary members
to defect from the opposition. Three more defectors from the GNP
will break the opposition's control of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The GNP, which lost last year's presidential elections due to
its then ruling government's economic mismanagement and an
infighting-induced split, continued exhibiting its political
shortcomings in the local elections.
</P>
<P>
"The GNP's failure in the local elections showed that South
Koreans are behind the Kim Dae-jung's government at the time when
the nation is in grave economic troubles," said an official of the
ruling camp after the local elections.
</P>
<P>
"The ruling coalition's sweeping victories in Seoul and its
surrounding Kyonggi and Inchon areas are seen especially as
continued support for Kim's efforts to overcome the crisis," said
a political analyst of Yonhap News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The population in Seoul, Kyonggi and Inchon accounts for nearly
one-third of the total population of the country.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for the United States for a nine-day state visit
Friday, President Kim said he will speed up his reforms, including
reorganization of political parties, upon his return from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"To take the fate of our country into our own hands and carry
out economic reform effectively, I must say we have no choice but
to make active efforts for the reorganization of political
parties," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
With the triumph in the local elections, Kim will push ahead
with strong restructuring of politics and the economy to the
extent that satisfies South Koreans and the international
community, said the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
