<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Killed During Fighting in Baidoa, Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 18 people were killed
and more than 25 others wounded as heavy fighting continues for
the third day Friday over the control of the important south
Somali town of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
The fighting pitted the Rahanwein Resistance Army militiamen
(RRA) against those of Hussein Mohamed Aidid's faction and most
of the deceased were killed inside the town.
</P>
<P>
In the latest development, about 150 heavily armed militiamen
from the RRA forces launched a tactful attack on two fronts, one
on the town of Baidoa itself while the other wing, about 100 more
militiamen, had cut off the road between Mogadishu and Baidoa at
Manyafulka bridge, 7 km south of the town, to block any possible
reinforcement from Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The RRA attack had penetrated into the defense positions of
Aidid's men in the town of Baidoa Thursday night with
face-to-face clashes. Aidid's men merely maintained control of
the former presidential palace of the town while the RRA men
managed to take control of the rest of Baidoa. Militiamen from
both sides claimed to have inflicted heavy casualties on the
other.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the VHF radio reports Friday morning,
another fierce fighting broke out again in and outside the town.
Sources close to the militiamen of Hussein Aidid said the RRA men
were driven out of Baidoa toward their former militia bases
outside the town.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the RRA men still maintain the bridge of
Manyafulka which is a strategic point for the connection of
Baidoa to the capital.
</P>
<P>
The reason why the animosity had renewed among the two sides
is not known. However, RRA spokesman Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle
said his men are motivated by the escalated looting and armed
robbery by Aidid's men on the Rahanwein people in the town.
</P>
<P>
This renewed hostility might also jeopardize the possibility
of the convening of the national reconciliation conference in the
town of Baidoa which is supposed to take place within three
months, according to an agreement of the faction leaders here in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
About 50 people are known to have died and more than 70
others, mainly civilians, are believed to have been wounded since
the fighting renewed three days ago. So far there's no official
word from Hussein Aidid's side over the fighting.
</P>
<P>
However, Aidid's top lieutenants characterize these serious
clashes as habitual minor incidents, skirmishes and hit-and-run
attacks by the RRA which would not hurt the stability of the town
nor affect the current peace movements in Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0112 </DOCNO>
