<HEADLINE> Bulls Faces Tough Time in NBA Game 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- After losing four playoff games
and down 0-1 to the Utah Jazz, the Chicago Bulls seem to be in big
trouble heading into Game 2 of the NBA Finals later tonight in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Rodman, who said he liked the nightlife of Las Vegas,
got a green light from coach Phil Jackson, taking an overnight
trip to the gambling city just hours after Wednesday night's 88-85
overtime loss.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan kidded that some of his coach's spiritual
serenity is wearing off on the players.
</P>
<P>
"We're practicing smiling when we may be frustrated inside so
we can relieve some tension. It's an art form. It takes about 10
years."
</P>
<P>
A loss tonight would drop the Bulls to 0-2, a place Chicago has
never been in its run to five titles in this decade.
</P>
<P>
"I have an inner confidence about ourselves and what we are
capable of accomplishing," Jordan said. "One game does not
deteriorate like that. It's the ultimate apex of the season, but
you don't fight that apex with anger and frustration."
</P>
<P>
Jeff Hornacek will start out guarding Jordan. Bryon Russell
and Shandon Anderson also will get their turns.
</P>
<P>
Hornacek insists he feels fine, but he looks as if his sore
Achilles' tendon is bothering him. Jordan is glad to feel that.
</P>
<P>
In Game 1, the Bulls got almost nothing from anyone other than
Jordan and Scottie Pippen. Toni Kukoc had a tough shooting game
and is counted on for a better showing tonight.
</P>
<P>
After tonight's game, the series shifts to Chicago's United
Center for Game 3 on Sunday. 
</P>
