<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts International Wildlife Film Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The first international wildlife
film festival opened at the Great Hall of the People here today to
commemorate the 26th World Environment Day, which falls today.
</P>
<P>
The '98 Wildscreen China Film Festival, jointly sponsored by
the State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA) and the
World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF), will feature 10 award-winning
documentaries.
</P>
<P>
The event is the first time that Wildscreen has held a
retrospective of its award-winning films outside England. Since
its founding in 1982, the biannual Wildscreen Festival has become
the world's most authoritative forum for nature and wildlife
film-making. Bristol, the home of Wildscreen, has often been
called the "Green Hollywood."
</P>
<P>
The festival's organizer said that Wildscreen is screening its
best documentaries in a bid to spread environmental knowledge and
improve the public's environmental awareness through the film
festival.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day festival, the China Film Archive will show
the documentaries free of charge to the public.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to make Wildscreen China a success, the Shanghai
Television Corporation (STV) will broadcast some of the
documentaries.
</P>
<P>
Also in the period, SEPA, the World Wide Fund for Nature
and the China Television Documentary Association, will
hold a two-day international symposium to discuss the development
of wildlife film production in China.
</P>
<P>
The festival is sponsored by the US-based Johnson and Johnson
Group, which has donated more than 1.3 million yuan to help China
carry out research into endangered wildlife protection over the
past four years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
