<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Hails Rescheduling of Private Sector Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (BI) expressed here
Friday warm welcome to the rescheduling of the country's private
sector foreign debts, reached with international creditors
recently.
</P>
<P>
"Our wish has come true. This is a significant way of solving
our private sector debts, including our banking debts," said BI
Governor Syahril Sabirin.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and 13 foreign banks reached in Frankfurt, Germany,
on Thursday a debt rescheduling agreement involving dozens of
billions of U.S. dollars in credit owed by the country's banking
sector and private companies.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed after four days of negotiations,
Indonesian banks would be offered an extension of up to four years
in the repayment of 9.2 billion dollars of short-term debts due by
the end of March 1999.
</P>
<P>
The deal also foresees the creation of a rescheduling agency to
help Indonesia's private companies get a grip on their foreign
debts which are estimated at about 60 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
