<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Issues Environmental Bulletin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region witnessed
sound environmental conditions in 1997, despite pollution and
ecological damage in some areas, according to an environmental
bulletin issued by the Regional Environmental Protection Bureau
today.
</P>
<P>
The indices of sulphur dioxide, and nitrogen and oxygen
compounds in the air of Lhasa and Xigaze cities and Qamdo Town all
meet the national air quality criteria.
</P>
<P>
The region suffered no acid rain last year.
</P>
<P>
The water quality of major rivers in Tibet was consistently
good in 1997, with the indices of phosphorus and heavy metals in
the water reaching the national criteria for surface water. In
addition, the drinking water in major cities and towns was found
to be up to standard.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin reveals that Tibet reclaimed 1,429 ha of farmland,
planted trees on 6,667 ha and developed 343 ha of grassland last
year. However, about 11.4 million ha of grassland, 17.2 percent of
the region's total, had deteriorated by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The region now has 13 nature reserves, with a total area of
325,000 sq km.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
