<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- More European Union (EU) countries have refused to
impose an estimated 20.6 percent anti-dumping fees on Egyptian
textiles, the Middle East News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Hakim Hagag, head of the Holding Company for Textile
Weaving, was quoted as saying that these countries include
Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, Finland, Denmark and
Germany. They joined other EU members including France, Spain,
Portugal, Greece and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU quota, Egypt can export 20,000 tonnes crude textile
to these countries annually worth 400 million Egyptian pounds
(about 118 million U.S. dollars). In fact, Egypt's annual exports
of textiles and off-the-peg clothes to Europe exceeds 3 billion
pounds (882 million dollars). The quota is affected specially
after the EU's imposition of the anti-dumping fees in April.
</P>
<P>
Hagag said that an international lawyer has been authorized to
plead against the anti-dumping fees before the end of June.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Libya have signed a set of pacts on boosting
media, cultural, maritime transport, agriculture, health and
industrial cooperation, according to the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The most outstanding of the agreements, which were signed at
the Egyptian-Libyan Higher Committee meetings, was the
establishment of joint ventures on manufacturing automotives,
building materials, household appliances, in addition to promoting
real estate and tourist investments.
</P>
<P>
It has also decided to start joint operation of factories in
Libya such as those of textile, leather, food and car tires.
</P>
<P>
The committee also underlined the resolve to conduct joint
surveys of mineral resources, implement railway and electric
power grid projects and conduct gas and oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has paid back a total of 4.496 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign debts between January 1 and June 3 this
year, according to newly-released official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, 3.437 billion dollars were paid by the Turkish
Treasury, 141.1 million by the Central Bank, 872.6 million by the
Ministry of Defense and 45.8 million by the Turkish Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's foreign debt was put at 84 billion dollars by the end
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Moroccan Fund for Social Security, a public
establishment run by trade unions, has initiated an extensive
publicity campaign to urge companies operating in Morocco to
settle their arrears in the best interest of their employees.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic-language daily Al Hayat quotes a spokesman of the
fund as saying that over one million workers in Morocco do not
enjoy the system of social insurance and pensions, an issue which
causes grave damages to workers and Moroccan economy as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
