<HEADLINE> Monument Erected to Mark U.S. Air Force Heros in WWII </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony was held today in Xing'an
County of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region to unveil a monument
in memory of the l0 U.S. air force heroes who died 54 years ago in
the World War Two.
</P>
<P>
A B-52 bomber with 10 crew members aboard was crashed in the
return journey after bombing the Japanese warships harbored in
Taiwan on August 31, 1944. The whole team were passed away at the
accident.
</P>
<P>
Some 52 years after the crash, two local farmers found the
remaining parts of the plane. Local government, along with staff
from the United States, found bones or badges of the crew in the
later excavations.
</P>
<P>
The 2.6-meter high 3-meter wide granite monument was
constructed in a park some 2,000 meters away from the spot. The
inscription on the monument recorded the deed and the names of the
late heros.
</P>
<P>
In the ceremony, local officials and a military representative
from the U.S. embassy in China made speeches to praise the heroic
behavior of the U.S. youngers.
</P>
<P>
The monument is co-founded by the Guangxi Government and the
Guangxi Military Command.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
