<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Imposes Censorship on War Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga Friday used emergency laws to impose a censorship on
domestic and foreign media coverage of the country's civil war,
according to a news release from the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary C. de Silva said in the release that the
regulation on the "emergency prohibition of publication and
transmission of sensitive military information" went into effect
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government imposed a similar censorship in April
1996, but lifted it in October of that year.
</P>
<P>
A similar censorship on Colombo-based foreign media was also
imposed in September 1995, but within four days the authorities
ended the restriction for the foreign media but upheld it for
local publications.
</P>
<P>
The latest government move came a day after heavy fighting
broke out in the north of the island country, in which both
government troops and Tamil rebels claimed to have caused heavy
losses to the other side.
</P>
<P>
The release said any report about military operations without
the approval of the censor will constitute an offense punishable
under the emergency laws which allow the authorities to detain the
suspects for long periods. Army Deputy Chief of Staff Jaliya
Nammuni was appointed by the president as the chief censor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
