<HEADLINE> Blatter Says Havelange Likely to Stay in Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- FIFA president Joao Havelange could
stay in power for another two years, said FIFA presidential
candidate Sepp Blatter here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Blatter, currently the FIFA sectretary general, said he had not
excluded the possibility that the 82-year-old Havelange may be
asked to stay on,
</P>
<P>
"It could happen," said Blatter. "We have considered it and
have not ruled it out."
</P>
<P>
Blatter and UEFA president Lennart Johansson, has been locked
in a two-way battle to take over the most powerful job in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Their struggle threatens to tear football apart and in order to
heal the wounds Havelange would be asked to delay his retirement.
</P>
<P>
Senior FIFA insiders have also refused to dismiss the idea that
Havelange, who has ruled world soccer iron-handedly for the past
24 years, could still be president when the congress finishes on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a lot of nasty things said in the battle
between Blatter and Johansson. It is not good for football and
getting Havelange to stay on could give time for the wounds to
heal," said one official.
</P>
<P>
Havelange has consistently denied the possibility he would stay
on but few people doubted he could be persuaded to change his mind
if the majority of congress were in favour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
