<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy in Better Shape: President-Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President-Elect Joseph
Estrada Friday said the Philippine economy is in better shape than
some of its neighbors which also suffered from the regional
currency crisis and the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with the finance managers of the
outgoing Ramos administration at the central bank building,
Estrada said the Philippines' inflation rate remains "manageable."
</P>
<P>
The National Office of Statistics announced on the same day
that the country's inflation rate in May rose sharply to 9.2
percent from April's 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who had vowed to examine the status of the national
treasury, said the incoming secretaries of the Department of Trade
and Industry, the Department of Finance and other finance experts
will study whether there is a need to change the inflation rate
target of 7 to 8 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada said there is nothing to worry about the
amount of foreign debts his administration will have to face.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the country's total foreign debt had
reached 45 billion U.S. dollars as of the end of last year.
However, only 9 percent of the debts were classified as public
debts and the remaining were recorded as private debts.
</P>
<P>
Estrada expressed optimism that his administration will be able
to fulfill its financial obligations, particularly the settlement
of short-term debts which represent 18.6 percent of the foreign
loans incurred.
</P>
<P>
"We have a better chance of reviving our economy, compared to
our neighbors in Southeast Asia," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the Philippines is the least affected in
the regional financial crisis and would first come out of the woes
in the second half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
