<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Urges Palestinians to Continue Fighting for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Friday called on the Palestinian people to
continue their struggle for peace, self-determination and the
return of their homeland.
</P>
<P>
The call was issued in Gaza by the PNA in a message marking the
31st anniversary of the 1967 War, the Jerusalem-based Palestinian
news service Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC)
reported.
</P>
<P>
During the Six Day War in 1967, Israeli forces captured the
Palestinian territories of Gaza Strip and West Bank as well as
Syria's Golan Heights and Egypt's Sinai Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"The anniversary comes at a time -- the Israeli mentality of
expansion remains the same and Israel continues to reject
implementing the United Nations Resolutions 242 and 338 relating
to the Arab-Israeli conflict," the message said.
</P>
<P>
Despite its acceptance of peace negotiations, the current
Israeli government refuses to commit itself to the peace process,
particularly the land-for-peace formula, and rejects implementing
the signed agreements with the Palestinians, it added.
</P>
<P>
The PNA slammed Israel for continuing "its attempts to
judaize Palestinian lands which it occupied in 1967 through the
settlement campaign and the occupation of Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
It also warned Israel that the failure to achieve a
comprehensive and just solution to the Palestinian issue "means
the continuation of waves of violence and conflicts."
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat is scheduled to convene a weekly
PNA Cabinet meeting Friday evening in Gaza to discuss the latest
political developments in the region, his push for convening an
Arab summit to confront Israeli intransigence and the
international efforts to revive the peace process, JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has just returned from visits to Oman, Yemen and Jordan
as part of his continued campaign to hold an Arab summit to
pressure Israel to carry out the long-delayed further troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
While most Arab leaders have agreed in principle to attend such
summit, no agreement has been reached on when, where and how it
would be held due to the differences among the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several other Palestinian parties and movements, such
as the People Party and the militant movement Islamic Jihad (Holy
War), also issued statements Friday, calling on Palestinian people
to continue their struggle until achieving national independence,
or the establishment of an independent Palestinian state with
Jerusalem as the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
