<HEADLINE> Ramos Accepts Solicitor General's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Philippine President Fidel
Ramos Friday accepted the resignation of Solicitor General Romeo
de la Cruz who sought the acquittal of former First Lady Imelda
Marcos.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Ramos designated Justice Secretary Silvestre
Bello III to replace de la Cruz on June 8.
</P>
<P>
De La Cruz Wednesday asked the Supreme Court to acquit Imelda
of her 12-year jail sentence for corruption handed down in 1993
and upheld by the Supreme Court in January this year.
</P>
<P>
The solicitor general made the appeal six days after submitting
his letter of resignation to President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
"I leave the Office of the Solicitor General with deepest
sorrow, for I have been with this office since 1974, starting as a
solicitor and rising through the ranks to my present position," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Accepting de la Cruz' resignation, Ramos said he has exercised
his prerogative to make the effective date of the chief government
lawyer's resignation earlier.
</P>
<P>
"In your departure from government service, I am certain that
your deep sense of civic duty will remain and that, in your future
endeavors, you will continue to support our common vision of
Philippines 2000," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Former First Lady Imelda was appealing to the Supreme Court for
acquittal while on parole. She ran for the presidency but quit a
few days before the voting day on May 11, calling on her
supporters to vote for Vice President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, the presidential candidate of the main opposition, the
Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses), won overwhelmingly in the elections. He will assume
office on June 30 when Ramos' term expires. 
</P>
