<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian King Warns Against Foreign Dictatorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Supreme Head of
State King Tuanku Ja'afar Friday warned against foreign powers
dictating the fate of the nation.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the time for the people to give up hope and to let
foreign powers dictate the fate of the nation," the king said in
his 75th birthday address to the nation broadcast over radio and
television Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The king said the country's currency, the ringgit's
depreciation and slump in the stock market, resulting from "moves
designed by foreigners," were unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
Tuanku Ja'afar said the level of advancement and economic
might, not the size of the military, that determines a country's
strength, holds true today as foreigners apply their economic
powers to crippling developing economies like Malaysia and
destroyed whatever progress the nation has achieved thus far.
</P>
<P>
Tuanku Ja'afar said that in the wake of the country's economic
problems it is crucial that all parties preserve the prevailing
unity and refrain from compounding the difficulties by creating
ill feelings toward each other.
</P>
<P>
"Now it is not the time for us to be selfish. We should be
helping each other to go through the current hard times as we'll
only be a strong society if we are all united," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Malaysians to increase productivity and give
full backing to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad in steering the
country toward a full recovery from the current economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"I am very much satisfied with all the efforts being undertaken
by the government under the leadership of the prime minister," he
said. "I believe and am confident that the bold and firm steps
initiated by the government will bring good to the people and the
country."
</P>
<P>
Tuanku Ja'afar said he is pleased with the people's support for
the government's endeavors toward that end so far and reminded
them that the current situation calls for sacrifices and thrift on
their part.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to be spending like the way we did before.
Instead we should strive to increase national savings to
consolidate the country's reserves. It is my hope that all
Malaysians remain patient in going through this tribulation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The king said that for continued national prosperity,
Malaysians should be constantly sensitive to the customs and
religious peculiarities of the various racial groups so that
harmonious coexistence and tolerance could be preserved and
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The current economic problems should not be an excuse for
remaining inert but should instead prompt the people to put in
greater efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
The king also advised the Malaysians to attend to and check
issues which are often linked to economic collapse from causing
the social fabric to disintegrate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
