<HEADLINE> China Intensifies Treatment of Industrial Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China has redoubled its efforts to
treat industrial waste in the past year, according to the latest
report of environmental situations of the country.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of waste water was treated last year, and near
89 percent of waste gas was cleaned by removing dusts, said the
annual report from the State Environmental
Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
The recycling rate of solid waste was 45.2 percent, a rise of
2.2 percentage points over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country spent more than 50 billion yuan (six billion US
dollars) on pollution control and treatment projects last year.
</P>
<P>
Included in a national "Cross-the-Century Greening Plan", a
total of 180 projects to control water and air pollution and to
treat solid wastes have been completed, involving 10.66 billion
yuan in investment.
</P>
<P>
An additional 520 projects are under way, involving a total
investment of 17 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China produced 41.6 billion tons of waste water in 1997,
including 22.7 billion tons of industrial waste water.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of discharged sulphur dioxide exceeded 23
million tons last year, 80 percent of came from factories.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 million tons of dust were discharged, and 160 million
tons of industrial solid waste were produced at the same time,
said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
