<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Fall On Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to fall on
the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) lost another 19.28 points to close at 1168.46 points
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices went lower on widespread selling
by foreign investors eyeing plunging regional currencies on the
one hand and a hike in UK interest rates on the other.
</P>
<P>
"There was selling of property and bank shares from Japan,
Britain and the United States," one dealer said. "It was a
combination of short selling and dumping," the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
A 25-basis point hike in UK interest rates to 7.5 percent from
7.25 percent weighed on investors' minds, he added.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume dropped marginally to 112.97 million
units, valued at 207.6 million Singapore dollars (about 122.84
million U.S. dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 215 to 73,
while 303 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Land was the most actively
traded stock as it registered a turnover of 8.27 million units. It
was followed by local computer maker IPC which had 7.76 million
shares traded. Easyknit was next with 6.7 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
Oriental led the gainers of the day as it rose by 19 cents to
finish at 3.08 Singapore dollars. SeaView increased by 10 cents to
end at 4.1 Singapore dollars. Singapore Land was up by eight cents
to close at 3.06 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Genting 200 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.7 dollars to end at 4.1 Singapore dollars. Local
computer sound card maker Creative 50 fell by 70 cents to close at
29.3 Singapore dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) was down by
50 cents to finish at 12.6 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
