<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Lackluster Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Disappointed a rate cut was now
not on the agenda, the Australian sharemarket followed its weekly
trend by closing lower Friday with buyers remaining sidelined
ahead of a weekend.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 15.6 points down at 2642.8 in
tepid trade, with financial sector stocks notably weaker.
</P>
<P>
"It was a lackluster day. Just about every day this week has
been the same. People are really uncertain now and just sitting on
their hands," Hartley Poynton broker Craig Sharpe said.
</P>
<P>
Comments by Reserve Bank of Australia governor Ian Macfarlane
overnight effectively killed off lingering hopes of an interest
rate cut and contributed to Friday's poor market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 30.5 points down at 4595.4,
with the banking index slipping more than one percent.
</P>
<P>
Leading the fall among the major banks was Westpac, which
dropped 25.6 cents, NAB dropped nine cents, ANZ was 8.7 cents
weaker, while Commonwealth fell 27.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
Retailer Coles Myer finished at its lowest level since November
1997 after losing another seven cents. Manufacturer Email
recovered from a fall soon after announcing a 28 percent fall in
net profit.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index lost 3.1 points to 1074.2, with the
gold sector finishing the week down after a fluctuating five days.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lost 13.9 points to 1114.1.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 221.76 million shares worth 671 million
Australian dollars (416.02 million U.S. dollars) with falls of 546
ahead of 373. 
</P>
</TEXT>
