<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Israel's Coalition Crisis Looming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A new crisis is brewing in
Israel's coalition over the conversion bill, which reflects the
deepening social divide in the Jewish state caused by the
increased political weight by religious parties.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil was triggered early the week by the instruction by
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to the Knesset (Parliament) Law
Committee to advance legislation of the conversion bill, which is
pending the second and third reading in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which passed the first reading in the Knesset last
year, affirmed the monopolistic power of the Orthodox-dominated
Chief Rabbinate, the highest religious authority, to carry out
the conversions.
</P>
<P>
At least three coalition factions, the immigrant party Yisrael
Baaliya, The Third Way and Tsomet, have expressed strong
objections to the bill. Some lawmakers from these parties even
threatened to bring down the government, if the bill becomes law,
citing it will violate the civil rights of the secular population.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the Neeman Committee's recommendations be
adopted, either by agreement or legislation.
</P>
<P>
The Neeman Committee, led by Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman,
was set up due to the outcry from the American Jews raised
following the passage of the conversion bill on its first reading
last year.
</P>
<P>
Following intensive inter-religious consultations, Neeman
formulated a compromise solution to the conversion issue. He
proposed setting up a joint conversion institute, which is
composed of Orthodox, Reform and Conservative rabbis, to allow
would-be converts to conduct Bible and Judaism study in different
ways, although the actual conversions would be carried out only by
Orthodox rabbis.
</P>
<P>
However, the far-right coalition parties still rejected
Neeman's compromise and demanded the conversion bill be passed in
its original form. They also threatened to bring down the
Likud-led government if Netanyahu fails to maintain the Orthodox
monopoly over conversions.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is expected to make intensive efforts to soothe the
anger on the two sections within his government so as to avoid its
downfall. He softened his tone on Thursday, saying that he
supports anchoring in law the compromise adopted by the Neeman
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The looming crisis in Netanyahu's coalition over the
conversion bill exposes one of Israel's most fundamental divides,
the struggle for power between secular and Orthodox segments of
society.
</P>
<P>
Although nearly 70 percent of Israel's 5 million Jews are
secular, the Orthodox Jews have sole control over performing
marriages, divorces and burials for all Jews in the country.
</P>
<P>
The religious and secular Jewish communities in Israel are
virtually living in separated places and conducting their lives in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
In the religious neighborhoods, police have to close the
streets in Shabath, the Jewish weekend beginning from sunset
Friday to sunset Saturday, so to prevent the secular traffic from
interfering with the Oxthodox Jews' prayers.
</P>
<P>
Tensions and even violent clashes often flared up between the
two sectors, when the secular Jews tried to prevent what they
called the religious coercion and violation of their rights by the
other side. Last year, the religious communities succeeded in the
partial closure of Bar Illan road, a major street in northern
Jerusalem, following years of struggle marked by violent clashes
with police and secular protesters.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996 elections, three religious parties, all powerful
members of Netanyahu's government, drastically increased their
political influence by gaining 23 seats in the 120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The new-found weight by the religious parties also contributed
to the difficulties facing the Israeli-Palestinian peace process,
because they are the leading force that opposes relinquishing
Israeli control over the Palestinian territories, which they
termed as part of the Greater Israel gifted by God to the Jews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Still Below 61 U.S. Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Australia
(RBA) made a massive 1-billion-plus effort to brace the ailing
Australian dollar Friday but the currency stubbornly continued to
wallow below 61.00 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar sank to 60.51 U.S. cents and close to its
lows of 60.45 U.S. cents, well down from 61.10 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The RBA started buying in the foreign exchange market mid
afternoon Thursday and managed to procure a bounce for the
currency, from 60.80 to 61.50.
</P>
<P>
But the speculators had other ideas and drove the unit back
down.
</P>
<P>
It scrambled back to 61.00 U.S. cents in morning trade as the
RBA continued its efforts and the Reserve Bank's governor vainly
talked about the need to understand the Australian economy's
strong fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
But the respite proved brief and U.S. hedge and mutual funds
continued to dump the local unit.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State bank's chief economist Craig James said he
understands the bank's frustrations but added that it was wasting
its time fighting the trend.
</P>
<P>
"History is littered with the failures of countries defending
their currencies," James remarked.
</P>
<P>
"The RBA is fighting a losing battle if it throws 1 billion to
2 billion Australian dollars to support it. It should let it go,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
James said that the RBA was in a difficult position because it
did not have much recourse to higher interest rates to support the
currency.
</P>
<P>
Tim Crawford, economist with St. George Bank, was a little more
encouraged by the Reserve Bank's support of the currency Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
"It may be only a slight kick higher but it has slowed a
downtrend," he said.
</P>
<P>
AAP chief economist Garry Shilson-Josling said the RBA had not
necessarily failed in its attempt to support the Australian dollar
overnight.
</P>
<P>
"The Aussie is still weak in spite of the intervention, but
even if it does slip lower over the next week or so that won't
mean the intervention has failed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The RBA last intervened in May and January, when the unit
touched 61.69 U.S. cents and 63.18 respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates Friday, the local currency was nearly steady
but weakened against the German mark. It fell to 84.42 yen from
84.45 and to 1.0715 marks from 1.0792. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
