<HEADLINE> Britain to Close Down a Nuclear Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The British government confirmed
Friday the reprocessing at Dounreay nuclear plant in the north of
Scotland is to be closed.
</P>
<P>
John Battle, Energy Minister at the Department of Trade and
Industry, said there was no economic case for work in the plant to
continue over the longer term.
</P>
<P>
He said the plant hoped to complete the commercial reprocessing
work by the year 2006 and then stop working entirely.
</P>
<P>
Dounreay has been criticized over a number of incidents in
recent months that have aroused concerns about its safety. They
included a power failure that led to a shutdown of parts of the
plant.
</P>
<P>
Despite recent controversy about standards at the Caithness
plant, the government insists the operation was still "safe."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Scottish Secretary Donald Dewar's office said
earlier in the day that Dewar would make an announcement in
Edinburgh on Friday morning concerning the closure of the plant
along with Battle.
</P>
<P>
Pressure has been mounted for the shutdown of Dounreay plant
after recent official report said 170 kg of enriched uranium was
missing in the late 60s. The report has aroused fears among local
people in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Tony Blair on Wednesday denied claims
that weapons-grade uranium had gone missing from Dounreay.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament that the apparent loss of 170 kg of the
material from the Dounreay plant was merely a case of poor
accounting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
