<HEADLINE> Woodcut Exhibition In Memory of Modern Chinese Art Forerunners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Central Academy of Fine Arts
(CAFA) staged today an exhibition of woodcut works by late artists
Li Hua and Gu Yuan who are known as forerunners of modern woodcut
art in China.
</P>
<P>
The two artists, both natives of south China's Guangdong
province, played a leading role in the new cultural moverment
during 1920s and their works depicted social realities and
people's lives before and after the founding of new China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Gu Yuan was the former CAFA president, and Li Hua was the
former director of the CAFA Woodcut Department for 33 years.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the exhibition today, Li's family
members donated to CAFA all his woodcut works, his manuscripts and
private collections of art pieces and books.
</P>
<P>
They also set up a fund with the awarded 150,000 yuan (about
18,750 US dollars) for the donation to support those who
contribute to woodcut teaching and creation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
