<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament Enacts Amended Peacekeeping Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Councillors (the
upper house) on Friday approved and enacted a bill to allow
Japanese peacekeepers abroad to use weapons for self-defense on
the order of a commander in the field rather than by their own
individual discretion.
</P>
<P>
The law will go into effect in July as it has already cleared
the House of Representatives (the lower house).
</P>
<P>
The bill, which amends the current U.N. Peacekeeping Cooperation
Law, was adopted by a majority with support from the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP), the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the
Komei, and the Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Communist Party (JCP) and the Social Democratic Party
(SDP) opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
The SDP opposed the amendment over concern it would contradict
Japan's constitutional ban on the use of force overseas.
</P>
<P>
Japan adopted the peacekeeping law in 1992, opening the way for its
Self-Defense Forces (SDF) to join U.N. peacekeeping operations abroad.
</P>
<P>
The current law, which leaves it up to each individual peacekeeper
to decide whether or not to use a weapon, has led to concern that
arbitrary use of weapons by individuals could disrupt the order of a
contingent and endanger peacekeepers' lives, government officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendment, the scope of peacekeeping operations is also
expanded to include election monitoring, not only by the United
Nations but also by regional organizations, such as the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Japan has sent its troops overseas for for several times since the
peacekeeping law was adopted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Welcomes Zimbabwe's Visa-free Arrangement for HKSAR Passport Holders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China Friday expressed
welcome to the decision of the government of the Republic of
Zimbabwe to grant visa-free access for a period up to three months
for holders of HKSAR passports.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the decision, which signifies the confidence of the
 government of the Republic of Zimbabwe in Hong Kong the HKSAR
passport," a spokesman for the SAR government said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was conveyed by the Zimbabwe Embassy in Beijing to
the Immigration Department of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Nationals of the Republic of Zimbabwe do not require a visa for
visiting Hong Kong for a period up to three months.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to welcome nationals of the Republic of Zimbabwe
to visit Hong Kong," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
