<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rate Soars in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The protracted Asian currency crisis
pushed the Philippines' year-on-year inflation rate to a high of
9.2 percent in May 1998 from 7.8 percent recorded in April, the
National Statistics Office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a report that all the commodity groups
registered higher year-on-year inflation rates except for that of
services whose 15.8-percent inflation in May dipped slightly from
15.9 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The May inflation rate was mainly pushed by the higher prices
for food, beverages and tobacco (FBT), and housing and repairs.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for the FBT group rose to 7.6 percent in May
from 5.4 percent in April and that for housing and repairs up to
11.5 percent from 10.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Autonomous Region of Muslim Mindanao posted the highest
inflation rate at 14.8 percent in May while Western Visayas region
recorded the lowest rate at 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
On a month-on-month basis, the inflation rate for May stood at
1.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
