<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Ruling Parties Win Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean ruling coalition won
10 of 16 electoral districts Thursday in local elections,
according to election results released by the Central Election
Management Commission on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The coalition, constituted by the National Congress for New
Politics (NCNP) and United Liberal Democrats (ULD), dealt a heavy
blow to the opposition Grand National Party (GDP) in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP won in Seoul, Keangju, Kyongi, North Cholla, South
Cholla and Cheju and the ULD seized Inchol, Taejon, North
Chungchong and South Chungchong.
</P>
<P>
The opposition GNP recaptured Pushan, Taegu, Ulsan, North
Kyongsang and South Kyongsang.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NCNP won 84 and the ULD took 29 of the 232 head
posts in small cities and counties.
</P>
<P>
The winners, from a total of 10,042 candidates, will start
their four-year term from July this year.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, 17,128,050 or 52.4 percent of the 32,537,815
eligible voters cast their ballots, which was the lowerest voter
turnout since 1961.
</P>
<P>
The low turnout was blamed on voters' political indifference
caused by the economic crisis and mutual mudslingings by
campaigners, said the commission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
