<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah to Reach Deal with Israel on Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's anti-Israeli Muslim group
Hezbollah, or Party of God, will soon conclude a deal with Israel
to swap the remains of a killed Israeli soldier for Lebanese
prisoners held in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Voice of the People radio quoted Lebanese security
sources as saying that over the past few days, intensive and
tough negotiations had been conducting between the two sides
through the mediation of France.
</P>
<P>
Secret swap negotiations have started since a dozen of Israeli
commandos were killed during a botched raid on north of Israel's
so-called security zone in south Lebanon last September.
</P>
<P>
Israel has agreed to return 50 Lebanese prisoners held inside
Israel and the remains of more than 40 Hezbollah guerrillas in
return for the remains of an Israeli soldier killed in the botched
raid, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese sources said that the current negotiations focused on
a Lebanese important figure held in Israeli jail. Hezbollah has
asked Israel to put him on the swap list while Israel has not
agreed, saying unless the group provides some information about
an Israeli pilot missing during the failed raid in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah and Israel first exchanged the remains of two
Israeli soldiers for the bodies of 126 guerrillas under a
German-brokered deal in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah has been fighting against Israeli
troops since Israel set up the 1,200-square-kilometer security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly protect its northern
borders from cross border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
