<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Children Prefer Books To TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A recent study by the China
Publishers Association has found that more Chinese children are
turning to reading as a way to spend their free time.
</P>
<P>
The study found that 43 percent of Chinese children say they
prefer reading books, while 34 percent prefer TV, and 21 percent
are particularly interested in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The study has gone some way in easing people's worries about
children being influenced by the electronic media.
</P>
<P>
In some developed countries, children are so obsessed with TV
that sociologists are afraid that they are becoming illiterate in
the electronic age.
</P>
<P>
The study of 7,000 children and their parents nationwide found
that some 70 percent of Chinese children spend 30 minutes to two
hours reading every day, and half of them read one to three books
a week.
</P>
<P>
It also found that Chinese children become interested in books
when they are two to three years old.
</P>
<P>
Parental behavior is a key to children's behavior, the survey
found, and 70 percent of the books read by children were bought by
their parents. Many parents begin to buy books for their children
when they enter kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
Most parents say that reading is one of the best ways to
increase children's knowledge, and they prefer getting their
children to read than watch TV or VCDs.
</P>
<P>
The study found that the natural sciences, fairy tales,
history, literature and the arts are subjects favored by Chinese
children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
