<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Vows Tough Measures for Tax Collection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
vowed Friday to take tough measures to collect taxes.
</P>
<P>
In a regular weekly radio address devoted to stabilizing the
country's financial market, Yeltsin said the tax policy would be
"maximally rigid".
</P>
<P>
"Time has come to demand and punish, up to criminal
responsibility," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that "taxes not collected are wages not
received by people."
</P>
<P>
Russia was hit by a financial crisis late last month and the
government cited the huge deficit, partly due to lax tax
collection, as one of the causes.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said Russia should learn from the west, "where failure
to pay tax is one of the most serious crimes."
</P>
<P>
The state "has the right to expect that citizens take a
responsible attitude to their duty as conscientious payers of
taxes," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for joint efforts by all without exception --
those in power, the industrialists, the bankers and the
rank-and-file citizens," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin pointed out, "problems can not be resolved
with tough measures only."
</P>
<P>
"There is the need to create an effective and flexible tax
system convenient for all -- both for the state and the taxpayer,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
To stave off the financial difficulties, the government has
taken a number of steps to cut spending. Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko announced a staff cut of 30 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
The government has also placed Eurobonds to raise funds.
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said Thursday that the country's
Eurobond placements this year might top 5 billion U.S. dollars,
much more than the earlier target of 3.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the financial crisis had been "noticeably defused"
but "the main work lies ahead".
</P>
<P>
"The development of the financial crisis poses a threat to the
stability of the Russian ruble and can entail price hikes and a
higher cost of living," Yeltsin said. "Of course we will not allow
this."
</P>
<P>
In his radio address, Yeltsin also criticized regional leaders
for housing themselves in posh mansions amid piling wage debts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
