<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Friday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The foreign ministers of the five permanent members of the
United Nations Security Ccouncil, which are also the world's five
officially recognized nuclear powers, Thursday issued a declaration
in Geneva calling on India and Pakistan not to make any more nuclear
and missle tests. They also agreed to cooperate to prevent a nuclear
and missile arms race in the Indian sub-continent and to reinforce
the treaty on non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
-- One day after the most grave train accident of Germany in 50
years took place, the German railway company Deutsche Bahn Thursday
put 60 first-generation fast speed ICE trains out of service. The
catastrophe of Eschede, which killed 94 people, could be caused by a
broken pad of wheels on a wagon located behind the motor-car.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- While the traffic of Air France remained disorganized, the
talks between unions of striking pilots and management resumed
Thursday evening. They were nearing an agreement on one of the
subjects of dispute -- the lowering of salary in exchange for the
company's stocks.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac Thursday attacked a plan introduced
by the left-dominated National Assembly to legalize ``contract
family,'' which would be made of a man and his mistress or between
homosexuals. He said that would ``denaturalize'' and ``trivialize''
the right of marriage, while promising to defend the role of
families in the French society as well as the Civil Code, including
the law on marriage. 
</P>
