<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Laid-off Women Get New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 6,000 female workers
discharged by industrial enterprises in northeast China's Liaoning
Province in the course of economic restructuring have gone in for
their own businesses in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Lang Fang, a laid-off woman, started a chicken farm where she
bred turkey introduced from the United States. In the past three
years, she sold out one million turkeys, 100 pigs and 1,300
chickens, netting an annual profit of 100,000 yuan (12,000 US
dollars). She was conferred the title of "re-employment star" by
the local government not long ago.
</P>
<P>
Another laid-off woman, named Tan Liping, went to Shenyang's
outskirtan area to develop edible fungus together with her husband
after she lost her job. Later the couple set up a bio-product
research center and passed on the cultivation technique to local
villagers.
</P>
<P>
In Changsha, capital of central-south China's Hunan Province,
10,000 female workers, or one seventh of the laid-off women in the
city, have found new jobs with the help of the municipal women's
federation at various levels.
</P>
<P>
So far, they have opened 14 training courses where 700
laid-offs have learned one or two skills, and half of the trainees
have new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
