<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell in Tokyo Friday as
upswings were capped by selling on rallies amid uncertainty over the
Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 103.04 points or 0.67
percent from Thursday's close to finish at 15,323.43.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 5.56 points or 0.46 percent to 1,201.94.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 280 million
shares, almost unchanged from Thursday's 278 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
With a lack of strong market-moving news, the Nikkei index drifted
in a narrow range throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
Market player sold stocks on rallies because they are still
uncertain about the Japanese economy, an analyst at a private
financial institution said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,336 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 656 to 424, with 180 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
