<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister to Visit Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai will visit Jordan Sunday for talks with King Hussein on
the peace process and bilateral security cooperation, a newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The English daily The Jerusalem Post said that details of
Mordechai's visit were finalized late Thursday night in
coordination with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's visit to Jordan was set following his talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Cairo Tuesday. This was seen
as part of the Israeli efforts to fend off the pressure from
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who has been lobbying for
support for holding an Arab summit to formulate a common strategy
to confront Israel's intransigent policies.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister, widely-considered the leading dove
within the right-wing Israeli coalition, insists on a
double-digit withdrawal from the West Bank. He said in Cairo that
the implementation of the second redeployment could no longer be
delayed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Knesset (Parliament) Wednesday, he warned
that the deadlock in the peace process is likely to lead to
confrontation and violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, upon his return from visits to Oman, Yemen and Jordan
on the push for an Arab summit, said Thursday in Gaza that he
hoped for a decision on the Israeli second withdrawal no later
than mid-June. He said that under the United States initiative,
Israel has to make the decision on the redeployment no later than
middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli newspaper reports, the U.S. has presented
its revised plan on Israeli redeployment, which would enable the
Palestinian side to control about 40 percent of the West Bank
following a three-stage pullbacks within 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Another issue top on the agenda of Mordechai's talks with
Jordanian officials will be security cooperation and joint efforts
to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has weakened its security ties with Israel since last
September when Israeli secret agency Mossad carried out a botched
assassination attempt to kill a Hamas leader in Amman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
