<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pegs Oil Prices To International Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A recent decision by China's State
Council on prices of finished oil products took effect today,
following a decision to peg crude oil prices to the international
market on June 1.
</P>
<P>
This is a final move to free China's oil industry from the
planned economy and the start of what may be fierce competition on
the international market.
</P>
<P>
According to new pricing system, the benchmark price of
domestic crude oil will be in line with the monthly FOB price plus
tariff of similar crude oil on the international market and will
be announced at the beginning of each month by the State
Development Planning Commission (SDPC). After China's oil prices
are pegged to the international market, the well-head price of
domestic crude oil will be about equal to that of imported
products, explains Huang Yan, General Manager of the China
National Petroleum Corp (CNPC).
</P>
<P>
The price of refined oil will be set by the SDPC in accordance
with the average prices of petrol and diesel oil in different
parts of the country and internationally. The retail price of
finished oil products will be announced by CNPC and the China
National Petrochemical Corp. (SINOPEC).
</P>
<P>
Crude oil, finished oil products, natural gas, chemical
fertilizers, and automobiles were strictly controlled by the state
after China started its reform and opening-up policy in 1978.
</P>
<P>
By bringing the price of crude oil and finished oil products in
line with international prices, China has demonstrated its
determination to increase its reforms and to open further to the
outside world, Huang says.
</P>
<P>
CNPC and SINOPEC were formed not long ago and are now two major
competitors in China's domestic oil market and they have
completely changed production, marketing, and domestic and foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
China is bringing its domestic oil price in line with
international prices at a time when they have slid to their lowest
point in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that this will bring with it
opportunities, but survival will be all the more difficult for
Chinese oil companies because they have to deal with domestic oil
market and price pressures as well as facing intense competition
from multinationals.
</P>
<P>
If they adapt, it will mean improved competitiveness for
domestic crude oil, a more standardized domestic oil market,
halting the smuggling of finished oil products, and changing the
difficult production and marketing process, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
They also say that the oil-price reforms this time will
completely change the long-standing government practice of setting
oil prices administratively in the planned economy and bring in a
new pricing system in line with international oil prices of the
market economy, which will have a major impact on the
market-awareness of oil and petrochemical companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
