<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, EU Plan Business Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Kenya's Export Promotion Council (EPC) have proposed a business
charter for raising the conduct of business to international
standards and restoring Kenya's trade reputation.
</P>
<P>
EU and EPC propose that the charter incorporates a code of
practice for all business and commercial contracts which would
establish a clear set of standards for the supply of goods and
performance of services, the East Africa Standard reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The charter would also raise expectations and change attitudes
concerning the transparency of contracts and accountability for
the use of resources in both public and private sectors,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"If it is to be effective, this charter would have to be
adopted and promoted at the highest levels of both sectors," said
a joint statement of EU and EPC.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that large improvements in policy
implementation to match the available policy framework were
needed.
</P>
<P>
"The charter, whose code of practice would include a statement
of principles with widespread application would also need the
full backing of the government," it said.
</P>
<P>
These principles would be adopted by all leading private and
public sector organizations and replicated with appropriate
adaptations by every concerned company and organization.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the companies and organizations dedicated to high
standards for the conduct of business, commerce and services
would be distinguished from those which did not adopt the
principles.
</P>
<P>
"A commercial contract reinforced with new legislation to
ensure proper accountability and transparency would be the prime
vehicle for the implementation and enforcement of the
principles," says the statement.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation is to ensure proper accountability and
transparency through provision for inspection and regular audit.
Proper arrangements for dealing with complaints and for seeking
legal redress in cases of dispute have also been recommended.
</P>
<P>
On the improvement of business ethics, the re-establishment of
a set of high standards for the conduct of business was passed as
the proper strategy.
</P>
<P>
It would be necessary to seek universal acceptance in both the
public and private sectors and to solicit a genuine commitment to
business ethics of the highest standards to be re-established in
consultation with the private and public sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The primary means of implementation would be through an
addition of a set of appropriate standards based on the agreed
principles to every business and commercial contract for both
domestic and export markets." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
