<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Children Urged To Eat More Dairy Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese nutritionists say that
children here need to eat more dairy products to improve their
general health, according to today's Guangming Daily, a national
newspaper designed for the country's intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
The paper printed an open letter from some of China's best
known nutritionists to Chinese parents reminding young mothers and
fathers not to forget to give some dairy products to their
children every day.
</P>
<P>
A national study found that a lack of calcium was one of the
biggest problems with nutrition here, and that per capita
consumption of calcium was only half the recommended amount.
</P>
<P>
China produces 7.34 million tons of dairy products every year,
only 1.6 percent of the world's total, and per capita milk output
in China is 6.6 kilograms, only one-sixteenth of the world's
average.
</P>
<P>
At the recent '98 China Milk Science Forum, specialists
suggested a "Dairy Product Operation" scheme that called for
improved dairy industry controls and increased raising of dairy
cattle and sheep to bring per capita milk products consumption up
to 20 to 30 kilograms in the not too distant future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
