<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of America Predicts U.S. Economic Trends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve will
hold off tightening even though the U.S. economy is booming, said
the Bank of America on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was made by the bank's executive vice president
and chief economist John Wilson and senior economist Frank
McCormick.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. economy grew at a robust 4.8 percent annual
rate in the first quarter of this year, it is expected to slow
down to 2.3 percent in the second quarter, causing the Fed to hold
off tightening monetary policy until this fall.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economic growth will likely rebound to 2.6 percent in
the third quarter and 2.9 percent in the fourth, as the negative
impact of the Asian crisis on the U.S. economy gradually wanes.
</P>
<P>
In response, they said, the Fed will push up the current
federal funds rate from 5.5 percent to 6 percent at year-end.
</P>
<P>
Although the current unemployment rate is clearly driving up
wage inflation, it has not yet caused an increase in consumer
inflation, said the two economists.
</P>
<P>
Although the Fed is increasingly worried about inflation picking
up sometimes in the future, Wilson and McCormick said, the current
inflation picture could hardly be better, and therefore there is
virtually no support in the political and business communities for a
Fed tightening.
</P>
<P>
This strong public sentiment against tightening, together with the
expected economic slowdown in the second quarter, will likely keep the
Fed on hold until this fall, they concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
