<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stock Market Fluctuates Over British Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus stock market fluctuated
sharply in the past week mainly due to a British newspaper's
negative report on political uncertainties on the island.
</P>
<P>
Despite the single-day gains of 6.2 points on May 29 led to the
CISCO All-Share Index to close at 426.6 points and enforced the
market's attempt to reverse decisively its last five weeks'
downward course, the market plunged on Monday by 8.5 points.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the market continued losing ground, but it regained
by 3.3 percent on Wednesday following favorable comments from
government public figures that prompted investors to return to the
market. On Thursday, the market continued the surge by rising 5.3
percent, with the CISCO All-Share Index closing at 423.2 points.
</P>
<P>
According to the weekly stock review released Friday by the
Cyprus Investment and Securities Corporation Limited (CISCO), the
sharp fluctuation in the stock market was due to another blow
dealt on investment psychology by an article published by the
British paper "Sunday Times" that insinuated adverse developments
on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that there is a British "contingency plan"
to airlift 250,000 people from Cyprus on fears over a war if
the Cypriot government goes on with its plan to deploy the
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles later this year.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus stock market has lost 10.6 percent since it started
declining at the end of April, containing this year's gains at
8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of transactions this week shrunk to 6 million
Cyprus pounds (about 12 million U.S. dollars), from 7.9 million
pounds (about 15.8 million dollars) the week before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
