<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Controls Substances Depleting Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The production and consumption of
substances that deplete the ozone layer is under restrict control
in China, according to the latest environmental situation report.
</P>
<P>
The increasing rate of the demand for substances harmful to the
ozone layer in China has been on the decrease since 1994, said the
annual report issued by the State Environmental Protection
Administration.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to November 1997, the Chinese government had made and
implemented more than 20 policies regarding ozone layer
protection. By the end of 1996, China had eliminated over 23,000
tons of ozone depleting substances.
</P>
<P>
The report said China by the end of 1997 had gained
international funds worth 270 million US dollars for over 230
projects to eliminate 60,000 tons of ozone depleting substances.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China will initiate a plan this year to ban the
production of Halon 1211 and Halon 1301, chemicals that deplete
ozone, by the year 2006 and 2010 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the annual production of Halon accounts for 14
percent of the country's total production of ozone depleting
substances.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
