<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Preparing For Large-Scale Dredging Of Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A pilot dredging project on China's
Yellow River that was completed today after half a year of work,
paved the way for a massive dredging project on China's second
longest river.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River silts up with sand and mud easily. So, the
project on an 11-kilometer and a 13-kilometer stretch in the
estuary in Shandong Province took mud out of the river and used it
to reinforce the embankment and to transform low-lying
saline-alkaline land. A total of 5.4 million cubic meters of mud
was removed.
</P>
<P>
This is different from methods used in the past. The Water
Resources Ministry worked out a plan to send 100 large dredgers to
remove silt. The Yellow River project alone is estimated to cost
16.99 billion yuan (2 billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Uses Nuclear Technology to Recycle Paper Mill Waste Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully applied nuclear technology in recycling waste water
from paper mills.
</P>
<P>
Scientists of nuclear fusion studies at the Sichuan-based
Southwest Research Institute of Physics attached to the China National
Nuclear Corporation developed a system that uses plasma to
purify and recycle paper mill waste water.
</P>
<P>
They said the system and research process are similar to that
of nuclear fusion studies. So far, only a few countries have the
technology.
</P>
<P>
The system has recently passed appraisal by experts.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said they can produce soda, carbon powder and
burnable gas from the waste water with the system.
</P>
<P>
They said the recovered soda could be reused for paper making
while the gas and carbon powder could be utilized either as fuel
or raw materials for chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
The disposed waste water will no longer cause pollution.
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Sichuan Province is to build a demonstration
factory to recycle paper mill waste water with the nuclear
technology.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the widely application of the system
could both benefit environmental protection and the production
of paper mills.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
