<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Z. Dollar Falls to Five-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar slumped
to the lowest level in five and half years on Friday after a
credit rating agency said it was reviewing the country's foreign
currency debt rating.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell over half a cent in trading with the American
dollar to crack the 52 U.S. cents mark, closing at 51.70 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
The sharp fall came after the international credit rating
agency Moody's said New Zealand's AA1 credit rating on foreign
currency bonds was on "review for downgrade."
</P>
<P>
The New York-based agency blamed New Zealand's growing current
account deficit - the difference between what a country earns and
spends internationally - for putting New Zealand on notice for a
downgrade.
</P>
<P>
A present, New Zealand' current deficit stood at 7.7 percent
of its GDP, and the Reserve Bank has predicted it would rise to
8.2 percent in the next half year before falling back to the
current level.
</P>
<P>
But Moody's indicated it was particularly concerned that the
deficit would remain at the current level for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
It said its review planned to focus on New Zealand's external
position, including any flow-on from Asia's financial crisis, the
strength of its domestic economy and the ability to boost savings.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
