<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plants 5.2 Million Ha of Trees Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China planted trees on an area of
5.2 million ha last year to put the country's total forest area at
130 million ha, according to China's newest environmental
situation report.
</P>
<P>
The forest coverage rate is near 14 percent according to the
annual report, issued by the State Environmental Protection
Administration.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China closed hillsides of 3.8 million ha to
facilitate afforestation. And more than 2.5 billion trees was
planted by Chinese volunteers last year.
</P>
<P>
China is going ahead smoothly with forest shelterbelt
construction in northwestern, northern and northeastern China, the
middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River and the coastal
regions, with more than two million ha of trees planted in those
areas last year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said China planted 260,000 ha of forests in the
middle reaches of the Yellow River, and the valleys of Liaohe
River, Zhujiang River and Huaihe River last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the report showed that China's forest area only
accounts for three to four percent of the world total, and the per
capita forest share in China is 0.114 ha, much lower than the
world average.
</P>
<P>
China's forests concentrate in northeastern and southwestern
areas, and timber forests are decreasing, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 35,000 ha of forests were damaged by fires
and seven million ha of forests suffered from plant
diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
