<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Successfully relocated 53 Endangered Plant Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Guizhou Province in southwest
China has successfully relocated and cultivated 53 kinds of
endangered plant species in its arduous efforts to build a
botanical garden.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country's endangered plant species concentrate in
the province on the eastern Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau. Of them, more
than 300 kinds are protected by the State.
</P>
<P>
Small in numbers and sporadically located, these precious
species's living conditions are worsening. The cycas under the
state first-category protection, for instance, is on the brink of
extinction, because of fragile living conditions.
</P>
<P>
To better protect the precious species, the province has
spent more than 700,000 yuan (about 87,000 US dollars) on building
a botanical garden in Longli County. Technicians are
sent to 26 natural reserves in the province to collect
seeds of the endangered species to relocat and cultivate
them in the garden.
</P>
<P>
As many as 120,000 plants of 53 varieties are growing in the
garden, including 11 kinds under state first-category protection
such as ormosia fir of the genus; 26 kinds under state second
category protection such as Taiwania flousiana; and 16
kinds of plants peculiarly growing in Guizhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
