<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Fall to 18-month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian Wool prices crashed
through the 600 Australian cents (roughly 372 U.S. cents) barrier
to an 18-month low at this week's sales, exporters said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said prices
plunged 2.5 percent on average at sales in Sydney and Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator slumped 16 cents to close at 584
cents a kilogram clean, the first time in 18 months the price fell
below 600 cents.
</P>
<P>
The western market indicator remained at 549 cents/kg as there
were no sales in Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
About 26.6 percent of the 60,486 bales offered were passed in.
</P>
<P>
"From the start of this season in July 1997, auction prices
have dropped by 15 percent on average in Australian currency terms
and by closer to 30 percent in U.S. dollar terms," the ACWE said
in its weekly wool report.
</P>
<P>
"To say that the price of wool today is very cheap in relative
terms would be an understatement, but this graphically illustrates
the weakness in global demand at the present time.
</P>
<P>
"Continuing to compound what is an extremely difficult market
environment are the problems associated with contractual defaults
where customers in a number of countries are now seeking
extensions of time to pay and renegotiation of prices under threat
of dishonoring contracts completely.
</P>
<P>
"This spreading 'disease' does nothing for maintaining
confidence or stability in international trading on wool," the
ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
About 52,921 bales are rostered for sale next week in Sydney
and Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
Wool brokers Wesfarmers Dalgety said in its weekly Wool Review
that the 600-cent barrier was generally seen as a resistance
level.
</P>
<P>
"Weak demand was unable to support the small rostered quantity
and the level of uncertainty within the industry continues to
increase," the review said.
</P>
<P>
But small rostered quantities over the next three weeks and
growing demand for high tensile strength fine wool could help
stabilize prices at current prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
