<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Capital Helps Promote Agriculture in Ningxia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Increasing inflow of overseas
capital is contributing greatly to the improvement of agricultural
production conditions and farmers' living standards in northwest
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A stretch of sandy wasteland, called Langpiziliang in Lingwu
county, for example, is now covered with lush green, alongside
with crisscross irrigation canals, fields, and newly-built houses,
due to a water diversion project from the Yellow River, financed
by 37 million US dollars of free-interest loans from the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The project, started in 1988, has by now helped cultivate more
than 33,000 hectares of irrigated farmland, resettled more than
50,000 farmers. And last year's grain output and farmers' income
in the areas went up 6 times and 90 percent, respectively,
compared with 1987.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, the region has implemented more than 20
aid projects from the World Bank, the World Food Program (WFP),
the European Union, Germany, and Japan, involving more than one
billion yuan-worth of overseas capital.
</P>
<P>
WFP provided free grain aid worth 3.7 million US dollars to
some counties, including the suburban area of the region's
capital, Yinchuan, to develop fish raising in wasteland-turned
fishing ponds. As a result, the city now ranks first in northwest
China in terms of per-capita aquatic products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
