<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Longest River May Suffer Heavy Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese water control experts
predicted that heavy floods are expected to attack the Yangtze
River, the longest in China, this year.
</P>
<P>
In the winter-spring period, the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River recorded more precipitation than ordinary
years. The river's mainstream reported two big floods in
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi, Hunan and other provinces along the river have entered
the flood season one month earlier. Southern provinces will be hit
by heavy floods in the June-August period.
</P>
<P>
State Anti-Flood and Anti-Drought Headquarters has issued a
circular, urging all provinces along the river to reinforce
embankments and improve water control projects.
</P>
<P>
Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Anhui and Jiangsu provinces have worked
out concrete measures to fight possible floods. People were
organized to repair existing water control facilities and build
new ones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
