<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, London Club Sign Pact on Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and the London Club of
commercial creditors have signed an agreement on rescheduling a
70-million-U.S.-Dollar debt, the East African Standard newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The signature formalizes a preliminary agreement reached on
February 12, Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP) was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In February, BNP, which led the negotiations, said that 31.2
million U.S. Dollars out of the total figure was in past-due
interest from January 1992.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan signed earlier this week, Kenya's principal
debt will be restructured into 10-year bonds, with a three-year
grace period.
</P>
<P>
That new bond will pay fixed interest of 3.5 percent for the
first four and half years and will pay the London Inter-Bank
Offered Rate (LIBOR) plus 13/16 percent thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the overdue interest will be forgiven and of the
remaining portion, 60 percent will be capitalized, or lumped into
the principal.
</P>
<P>
The rescheduled credits are all in U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
