<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Professor Praises Aid Projects in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- UNDP aid projects in China are doing
well, being properly managed, and reaching their goals, according
to Dr. Enjiang Cheng, an agronomy professor at Australia's
Adelaide University.
</P>
<P>
Cheng paid a week-long visit to a UNDP aid project in China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The local project officers are paid by the government, but they
work hard, are diligent, and help farmers, something that is
seldom seen in other countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cheng visited more than 20 rural ethnic minority families
during his tour and praised local project officers' efforts to
help poor farmers and teach economic management and new
concepts.
</P>
<P>
Trine M. Lund-Jensen, UNDP resident representative in China,
who accompanied Cheng during his Xinjiang tour, was of the same
opinion. She said that Chinese officials show great concern for the
common people.
</P>
<P>
Her colleagues had the same impression, as was demonstrated at
a meeting at the UNDP Headquarters late last year, where there
were positive comments on the projects in China, she said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP has aid projects in 134 countries, and China is the
largest recipient. The UNDP began five-year projects in China in
1979, with 220 million US dollars in funds. Then that sum went
down to 150 million US dollars in 1997, because of China's
improved national strength, she said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP has focused on poverty eradication, sustained growth
for agriculture, grain production, environmental protection, and
social and economic reforms, but it in the future will turn to the
poor in cities and women in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
It has a small-loan system for poverty relief, which was
introduced to China in 1991 and proved successful. The method is
now being expanded to all areas, said Zhang Ning, a Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation official.
</P>
<P>
"This is only one aspect of the success on China projects,"
Lund-Jensen said, "UNDP aims to gather the experience of every
country to form a new management concept, and make the new idea
work in local places."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
