<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import Cereals for Food Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is requiring
3.4 billion Shillings (about 55 million U.S. Dollars) to import
cereals so as to alleviate a food deficit in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
It is the second successive year that Kenya has been forced to
import food, following unpredictable weather conditions,
according to the latest Nafaka News, a quarterly newsletter of
the National Cereals and Produce Board.
</P>
<P>
"In the year 1996/97 crop season, the country had to import
maize and wheat following failure of the short and long rains, an
exercise which both the Board and the private grain dealers were
involved in," the newsletter said.
</P>
<P>
A government assessment on the effects of the El-Nino weather
phenomenon has found that most farms, especially those in western
Kenya, were affected, leaving a shortfall of seven million bags
(90 kms per bag) of maize, according to the journal.
</P>
<P>
In the long rains during the year, Kenya's net production of
maize and wheat stood at 22.7 million bags and 2.5 million bags
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
