<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enhances Efforts in Biodiversity Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China has scored rich achievements
in biodiversity protection after a decade of efforts, with the
number of giant pandas reaching 1,000, for instance, according to
the country's latest environmental report.
</P>
<P>
The annual report, issued by the State Environmental Protection
Administration, said that the number of state-level nature
reserves has reached 124, with 18 added last year.
</P>
<P>
The country has also set up more than 200 breeding centers for
rare and endangered animals, and 920-plus nature reserves of
different levels, covering an area of some 77 million hectares,
accounting for 7.64 percent of China's landspace.
</P>
<P>
The report said that China has built 870 forestry parks, 171
zoos and 111 botanical gardens, providing effective protection of
more than 6,000 kinds of animals and 1,000 kinds of plants,
including the Chinese alligator, the cathaya argyrophylla and the
dove tree.
</P>
<P>
Four reserves in China were included in the Northeastern Asia
Crane Reserve Network, and another three were included in the
Eastern Asia--Australia Wading Bird Reserve Network.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has fulfilled the requirements of
international treaties on biodiversity protection, and has
completed a report on China's biodiversity situation research and
a plan for its nature reserve development.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the countries with high biodiversity in the
world, with 30,000 species of higher plants, or one tenth of the
world's total, 250 species of gymnosperms, or 30 percent of the
world's total, and more than 6,000 species of vertebrates. In
addition, China has the world's biggest number in the kinds of
economic plants and domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out that the country's biodiversity
is facing a serious threat because of pollution and damage of
ecology.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 species of angiosperms, 60 species of gymnosperms
and 400-plus species of vertebrates are threatened with
extinction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Malaysia Targets Drug-Free by 2023 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has set a target that
by the year 2023, the country will be free from drug menace, for
which efforts are being intensified.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year plan involves a dual-pronged strategy to rid the
country of narcotic drugs -- one for reducing the demand for drugs
in the country and the other for cutting the sources for drug
supplies, Deputy Home Minister Ong Ka Ting said in an exclusive
interview with Xinhua recently.
</P>
<P>
In implementing the drug demand reduction strategy, Ong said
the stress is put on prevention, on awakening the public's
consciousness of drug menace.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary prevention entails creating drug-free schools first
which have been targeted to be realized within 15 years from now
on or by the year 2012, he said.
</P>
<P>
All primary and secondary schools throughout the country will
phase in the government's anti-drug preventive education program
for them first introduced in 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
The program, spearheaded by the National Drug Agency (NDA)
under the supervision of the Home Ministry with the cooperation of
the police's Narcotics Department and the Education Ministry,
stresses on developing resilience against the temptations of drug
abuse among the youth.
</P>
<P>
He said proper preventive education will give students a
knowledge of the danger of drugs and the strength of character to
resist drug pushers.
</P>
<P>
A committee under the NDA on preventive education on drugs also
published a booklet "Know Drugs and Fight Against Drugs" and
already distributed to more than 8,000 schools in the country,
which is a compulsory book for all the schoolmasters to read, he
said.
</P>
<P>
As for national prevention, activities such as exhibitions and
seminars are organized for the public participation to create
awareness of drug menace, in addition to anti-drug propaganda
through electronic and printed media, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government also planned to set up more than 80 service
centers at the county level to mainly provide consultations and
advises to people from all walks of life on how to get rid of
drugs or how to give up the bad habit of drug abuse, and half of
them are functioning, Ong said.
</P>
<P>
As part of the government's long-term plan to produce a
generation free from drug abuse by the targeted year, a new
program, dubbed "A Day With The Community," was initiated recently
to enable drug-dependent individuals or family members to
rehabilitate themselves from drug menace, he said.
</P>
<P>
The pilot project will be carried out throughout the country
step by step, first in urban areas, then the suburbs and the rural
areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government, which spent more than 517 million ringgit (over
200 million U.S. dollars) to tackle the menace between 1984 and
1995, has allocated in the 7th Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) 73
million ringgit (28.2 million dollars) to carry out anti-drug
activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Malaysia Targets Drug-Free by 2023 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ong said Malaysia is not a drug producing country, drugs are
mostly smuggled in from the Golden Triangle, and to cut the
sources of drug supplies, police and other law enforcing agencies
have beefed up guards along the Malaysian-Thai border and the
coastal areas against traffickers.
</P>
<P>
To outlaw drug trafficking, he said Malaysia amended its
Dangerous Drugs Act 1952 in 1983, which carries the mandatory
death sentence on conviction. Any trafficker who is arrested with
15 grams of heroin or 40 grams of cocaine or 200 grams of opium in
his possession will be charged under the mandatory death sentence
clause, 39(B) of the Act, Ong added.
</P>
<P>
The police narcotics unit was upgraded in 1997 to strengthen
its role as the main law enforcing body for better enforcement,
the deputy home minister said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a total of 36,284 drug offenders, of which 17,342 were
first-time drug addicts, were detected in the country, against
30,598 addicts, of which 13,846 first timers, arrested in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 13,159 drug traffickers were arrested
under various laws of the country, against a total of 11,361
traffickers arrested in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The seizures of drugs in 1997 were also higher than those in
1996. In 1997, drugs seized by the authorities concerned included
276.15 kilograms of heroin, 150.3 kilograms of opium (raw and
refined) and 3,889 kilograms of hemp, compared with 256.83
kilograms of heroin, 2.64 kilograms of opium (raw and refined) and
1,425.73 kilograms of hemp seized in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ong said the above-mentioned figures also showed that drug
abuse remains a serious problem in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said what is more worrying is that the majority of the
surging number of addicts are youths between the ages of 20 and
39, sapping the nation's manpower potential.
</P>
<P>
Drug addiction also harms the harmony of a family and the
society, results in more crimes as well as eats up the nation's
resources, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ong, there are now 12,500 drug addicts in 27
government-run drug rehabilitation centers nationwide costing the
government 4,400 ringgit (about 1,100 U.S. dollars) per addict per
year for treatment and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Ong called for cooperation of the whole society in tackling the
drug menace and sought international cooperation in curbing drug
smuggling into and out of the country to help Malaysia realize its
set target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sex Offenses up in Kenya: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Sex-related offenses are on the
increase in Kenya and there is need for a special police unit to
fight such crimes, according to Assistant Commissioner of Police
R.M. Kimundi.
</P>
<P>
As many as 334 cases of rape and 57 cases of defilement were
reported across the east African country in the past four months,
Kimundi said at a seminar ending Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day seminar on sexual offenses against women and
children, she also called for change in the law against abortion.
</P>
<P>
The seminar brings together judges, magistrates, lawyers and
women in the administration of justice.
</P>
<P>
During discussions, it was suggested that cases of sexual
offenses be investigated by women police officers, be heard by
women magistrates and be prosecuted by women prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
High Court Judge Justice Effie Owuor, who is also the
chairperson of Kenya Women Judges Association, called for the
enactment of laws governing marital rape.
</P>
<P>
Matrimonial rape ought to be criminalized, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Why should a person be hanged for robbery with violence while
those raping women and defiling children get away with lighter
sentences?" she questioned.
</P>
<P>
Police stations should be made more user-friendly and more
women officers should be trained to deal with victims of sexual
offenses, Owuor urged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
