<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educational Background of Rural Workers in Heilongjiang Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- As China's nine-year compulsory
education system spreads further afield, the educational
background of the labor force of northernmost Heilongjiang
Province has improved considerably in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of illiterate and semi-illiterate people in
Heilongjiang's work force has declined from 7.6 percent of the
total in 1996 to 3.7 percent now, according to an official survey
of rural people.
</P>
<P>
One of China's agricultural powerhouses, Heilongjiang has 17.29
million rural residents, almost half of the provincial population.
</P>
<P>
Some 51.5 percent of those surveyed have received junior middle
school education, up 9.2 percentage points from 1996. People with
senior middle school or higher education accounted for 10.8
percent, up slightly from two years ago.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, people with junior high school or
secondary vocational school education are mainly those in the
20-30 age group, while those with senior high school education
mainly belong to the 30-40 age group.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the relatively well-educated young people
will constitute the main force of Heilongjiang's rural workers in
the years ahead, a government official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
