<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Children Become Animal Guardians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Grade-three primary school pupil
Yao Rong happily became the "guardian" of a cub cheetah from the
Shanghai Wildlife Park recently.
</P>
<P>
He is among the first group of young animal lovers in China's
largest manufacturing city to be given the symbolic title "animal
guardian". What he is supposed to do is to donate part of his
pocket money to the care of the animal, and serve as its keeper
for one day. He and his family can visit the Park free of charge
for one year.
</P>
<P>
"I love cheetah, since it is the best runner of the animal
world," said Yao with a smile.
</P>
<P>
"The animals are friends of human beings. I hope all school
boys and girls show concern to them," he added.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held on June 1, the International Children's
Day, in the Park in the Pudong New Area, for Yao and five other
kids to become the guardian of a cheetah, a tiger, an elephant, a
lesser panda, a red-crest crane, and a giant panda.
</P>
<P>
The story all started with a 10-year-old girl, Xie Yi, who
wrote a letter to departments concerned expressing her desire to
help rescue the south China tiger which are said to be on the
verge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
The letter met with a favorable response from all walks of life
in Shanghai, leading to the decision of the Park to let small
animal lovers to choose animals to attend.
</P>
<P>
By drawing lots, 36 children were chosen to be the first group
of guardians.
</P>
<P>
"We want to further arouse the awareness of animal protection
among children in Shanghai through the activity," Gu Huikang, the
general manager of the Park, said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
