<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Concerns Over Political Uncertainty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The lingering concerns over
political instability are dying down in the Philippines as the
international community still kept a wary eye on neighboring
Indonesia following the forced resignation of former president
Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Political stability, a major merit in the first five years of
the Ramos administration, has returned to the Philippines with the
winning presidential candidate in the May 11 elections being
proclaimed timely last week, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been haunted by the specter of political
uncertainty since early 1997 when supporters of outgoing President
Fidel Ramos launched a drive to amend the constitution to allow a
second term for him.
</P>
<P>
The concerns over possible political instability eased in late
1997 when Ramos was forced to give up the attempt to amend the
charter and vowed to hold the May 11 general elections as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
But such concerns did not fade away as many people doubted that
the ruling Lakas-NUCD party, led by Ramos, would be willing to
hand over power to the opposition if their presidential bet lost
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to the elections, speculations mounted that there
could be no elections or a failure of elections because of
widely-expected massive cheating and widespread election violence.
</P>
<P>
The election jitters had sent the local currency and stock
markets tumbling for several weeks before the elections.
</P>
<P>
There were also prevailing concerns over another scenario that
the proclamation of the winning presidential candidate might be
deferred or even canceled if the popular but highly-controversial
opposition candidate, Vice President Joseph Estrada, led in the
race.
</P>
<P>
But the Philippines stood the test of the May 11 elections
which were held in an unprecedentedly peaceful and orderly manner.
</P>
<P>
And the official counting of votes was conducted in a
surprisingly smooth way, leading to the timely proclamation of
Estrada as president-elect last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that the May 11 polls highlighted the
country's political maturity which was achieved 12 years after the
demise of the 14-year-long dictatorship of former president
Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Both Ramos and the ruling party's presidential bet, Speaker of
the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia, should be accredited
much with the peaceful political scenario in the aftermath of the
elections, they said.
</P>
<P>
"President Ramos will bow out as one of the most admired chief
executives, having defied doomsday prophets who kept on harping on
alleged plots to perpetuate himself in power," a European diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who must step down on June 30 when his single
constitutionally-mandated six-year term expires, has done a lot in
guaranteeing peaceful, orderly and clean polls and keeping the
nation calm following the polls.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the May 11 ballots, seven major presidential
candidates signed a covenant for peaceful, orderly and clean polls
at the request of Ramos, playing a major role in stabilizing the
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
After the elections, Ramos sent out a strong message against
any major chicanery in altering the election results that would
have outraged millions of poor Filipinos who have pinned their
dreams on Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Because of Ramos' gesture, De Venecia, who accused the Estrada
camp of massive cheating, said that he would not block the
proclamation of frontrunning Estrada, virtually conceding defeat.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to Ramos' support, Congress finished the canvassing of
votes in three days and proclaimed Estrada as the winning
presidential contender last Friday, much earlier than many people
had expected, paving the way for a smooth transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, observers said that an agreement reached between
Ramos, de Venecia and Estrada on the establishment of "a
government of national unity" also contributed much to the current
peaceful situation.
</P>
<P>
Under the covenant, they agreed to forge a working coalition
between the ruling party and the Estrada-led main opposition LAMMP
(Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses) party, effectively preventing
any possible confrontation between the two camps.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Estrada's massive support gained in the
polls and his well-received initial cabinet line-up and political
and economic action agenda also helped the country achieve
political stability.
</P>
<P>
Estrada gained 39.8 percent support in the May 11 polls, giving
him a much broader mandate than that of Ramos who gained only 23.4
percent of votes in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In his initial list of cabinet members, Estrada appointed many
independent economists as his future cabinet men. He also promised
to adhere to Ramos-initiated economic reform policies, get rid of
graft and corruption, and lead the country out of the current
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
These moves have greatly eased concerns among the business
community which has doubted the ability of Estrada, a college
dropout, in governing the country, particularly its economic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of power is now well under way in the country. A
special committee headed by Ramos' aide Aguirre was created to
facilitate the transfer. Ramos himself is busy briefing Estrada
and his incoming cabinet on the country's economic, defense and
diplomatic affairs.
</P>
<P>
The local financial markets have reacted positively to the
peaceful political climate in the country. Despite the sharp
depreciation of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar in recent
weeks, the Philippine peso has been traded within the range of 38
to 40 pesos to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso, which had been stable for months, plunged to a low of
42 pesos to one dollar in the run-up to the May 11 elections
because of worries over political instability.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that the Philippine economy, which has been
overshadowed by fears of political uncertainty since the start of
the charter-change drive in 1997, will benefit much from the
stabilizing political situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Socio-economic Secretary Cielito Habito said earlier that the
smooth transfer of power, together with other favorable factors,
will help the slowing economy rebound in the second half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines posted a 2.5 percent growth in the gross
national product in the first quarter of 1998, much slower than
5.5 percent for the same period in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Thai Joint Move To Get Opium Growers To Change Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Thai drug control
experts reached an agreement recently to help Thai farmers get
away from raising opium poppies by teaching them to grow tropical
fruits.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-Thai joint venture will be established to get farmers in
the northeastern part of Thailand, part of the notorious "Golden
Triangle", to grow 1,600 hectares of dahlias to produce dahlia
juice for export.
</P>
<P>
This is another move meant to help cope with the drug problem
world-wide after the two countries began cooperation a couple of
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they will try to use dahlias as a substitute for
opium poppies in other parts of the Golden Triangle, if this pilot
project proves successful.
</P>
<P>
After decades of efforts, the area planted in opium poppies in
northern Thailand has gone from 20,000 hectares in the early 1960s
to less than 1,000 at present, according to Thai drug control
officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
