<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan Worked Out to Boost Thai Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- An action plan has been worked out
by Thailand's Export Development Committee to help accelerate the
country's sluggish exports, the Nation reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Committee chairman, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Commerce Supachai Panitchpakdi, said Thursday that Thailand should
adjust its strategy and focus on new markets like the Middle East
and should lay emphasis on growing markets like the United States,
Europe and China.
</P>
<P>
The action plan came after the poor performance of Thai
exports, which showed a minus 2.4 percent growth in U.S. dollar
term during the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The sluggishness was blamed mainly on the economic crisis which
has hit South Korea and Japan hard.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports to Japan in the first quarter of this year
fell 15.3 percent to 1.9 billion dollars from 2.2 billion dollars
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai exports to the United States increased by 18
percent to 2.8 billion dollars and to the European Union by 13.8
percent to 2.4 billion dollars during the same period.
</P>
<P>
The committee has also decided to make a greater effort in
improving troubled industries, mainly gems and jewelry exports.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said the opening of new export markets, easing
liquidity problems and enhancing the competitiveness of the
plunging industries were the three main strategies to help
accelerate exports.
</P>
<P>
He said the Commerce Ministry plans to organize a trade mission
to Japan in the second half of this year for talks with Japanese
executive-level officials to promote Thai goods and boost Thai
exports.
</P>
<P>
Similar trade delegations will also be sent to Eastern Europe
and the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
