<HEADLINE> Project to Be Launched to Create Rural Jobs in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Funding for the project, which is part of the 10 billion baht
(238 million dollar) social investment program, is expected to
come from the World Bank this July, the Nation quoted an official
from the Industry Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of the Rural Industrial Development Project
(PRID) will be implemented jointly by the government, private
sector and rural communities.
</P>
<P>
The project is distinguished in that it will create sustainable
jobs unlike other projects, such as construction of roads,
reservoirs and pathways.
</P>
<P>
Employment will continue after the project has been completed,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department of Industrial Promotion, the PRID
program will comprise 96 projects to create at least 3,000 jobs
that offer 3,000 to 10,000 baht (71.4 to 238 dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
The plan is considered economically viable since it is
estimated that it will put 341 million baht (8.1 million dollars)
into the pockets of rural people with an investment cost of 224
million baht (5.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Companies participating in the program will have the incentive
of a loan at a low interest rate of between 6 and 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented manufacturing sectors, such as garments,
jewelry, footwear and leatherware are targeted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
