<HEADLINE> World Bank to Grant 273 Million Dollars for Bangladeshi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to provide
a 273 million U.S. dollar grant for a road sector project in
Bangladesh, the second largest infrastructure project in the South
Asian nation after the 900 million dollar Jamuna Bridge, press
reports here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest credit from the donor agency for a single
project in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding in this regard was signed here
Thursday between Communications Secretary Syed Rezaul Hayat and
Arun Banerjee, the team leader of the World Bank Energy and
Infrastructure Unit.
</P>
<P>
The Third Road Rehabilitation and Maintenance Project, at an
estimated cost of 529 million dollars, include the construction of
a road, rehabilitation of a highway, development of a feeder road,
rehabilitation and reconstruction of a narrow bridge, and
procurement of equipment for training police.
</P>
<P>
Britain will give 23 million dollars in grant for the project,
which is expected to be started soon, with the rest of expenditure
coming from domestic sources. 
</P>
