<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicular Emissions Pollution Serious in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Vehicular emissions pollution in
New Delhi, capital of India, has become more serious, press
reports quoted a latest study as saying here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Vehicular emissions generated 64 percent of the total pollution
loads while 16 percent is generated by thermal power plants, 12
percent by industries and 7 percent by domestic sector, said the
study by the Central Road Research Institute (CRRI).
</P>
<P>
The CRRI also estimated that these vehicles account for 97
percent of hydrocarbons, 48 percent nitrogen oxide and 76 percent
carbon monoxide emissions in the air.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi vehicular population of approximately 3 million has
been distributed over a human population of approximately 10
million, indicating a high number of vehicles per million which
comparable to some of the cities of other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Traffic congestion and increased fuel consumption will lead to
further increase in emissions on the Delhi roads, the study
further said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reclaiming Land From Sea for Sewage Treatment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shanghai has reclaimed
120 ha of land from the sea as part of a second phase of a sewage
treatment project.
</P>
<P>
The land reclaimation, which took 15 months to complete, has
saved large amounts of farmland along with nearly 200 million yuan
(24 million US dollars) of investment, according to local
government sources.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the original plan, the project would cost
300 million yuan (36 million US dollars) and use a large strech of
arable land and mean moving some residents.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to lay a 40-km sewage pipe to collect industrial
sewages and human waste and to put it in the Yangtze River after
treatment.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to make it possible to handle 1.4
million tons of sewage every day, or a third of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
