<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Mediterranean FMs Commit to Regional Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALERMO, ITALY, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers from the
European Union and the southern Mediterranean basin ended their
two-day informal meeting Thursday with a commitment to regional
cooperation and security.
</P>
<P>
They said in a statement issued at the end of the meeting that
the process of Euro-Mediterranean integration that was decided
upon at the 1995 Barcelona conference would not be hampered by the
stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they said the European-Mediterranean cooperation
initiatives could have a beneficial impact on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference held after the meeting, British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook who is chairman of the meeting said that the
forum was characterized by "very full, open and constructive
dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said that the Palermo conference
revived the spirit of the first Euro-Med conference in Barcelona,
which saw the establishment of the Euro-Mediterranean Partnership
aimed at achieving a free trade zone in Europe and the
Mediterranean basin by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Europe hopes that economic growth in the southern Mediterranean
basin will help stem the flow of clandestine immigrants heading
north in search of work.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were 15 foreign ministers from the
European Union and 12 from the southern Mediterranean basin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shrinking Markets Prompt Looser Labor Export Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government is allowing
more businesses to export workers in a bid to revive the sluggish
labor market.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, Vietnam sent nearly
4,000 workers abroad, 800 less than the same period last year or
only 20 percent of the target set for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The severe Asian financial crisis is blamed for the sharp
drop. Japan and South Korea, the two biggest Vietnamese labor
importers, took a lot less Vietnamese workers this year because of
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to boost labor export, the government is to
promulgate a new policy under which qualified businesses, apart
from those which are state-run, will be allowed to deal with labor
export.
</P>
<P>
The government will also step up its control over 53 state-run
businesses which are engaged in labor exporting.
</P>
<P>
Laos is another big Vietnamese labor market, having attracted
more than 12,000 Vietnamese workers.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese and Lao governments have agreed to revise their
labor cooperation to boost exports in order to meet the demands of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 25,000 Vietnamese are working in more than 30
countries, with 11,000 in South Korea and about 4,000 in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
