<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Public Finance Reform in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved on
Thursday an interest-free credit equivalent of 63 million
U.S. dollars to help Bosnia introduce key reforms in the
management of its public finance.
</P>
<P>
The Public Finance Structural Adjustment Credit is the last of
eight operations financed by the World Bank during this fiscal
year from July 1997 to June 1998 to support the reconstruction of
Bosnia's war-ravaged economy.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to help the state and the entities prepare and
adopt budgets and develop debt management capacity.
</P>
<P>
It also seeks to help authorities address the issue of
transparency and accountability in government budgetary operations
as well as initiate reforms in two crucial areas of public finance
-- the harmonization of tax policies and administration and the
initial reform of the pension systems toward achieving financial
viability.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be provided through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessional
lending wing for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discovery Links With Mir Station In Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. space shuttle Discovery
successfully docked with Russia's Mir orbit station on Thursday
afternoon, completing its ninth and the last hookup in three years
with Mir.
</P>
<P>
During its four-day linking with Mir, Discovery will pick up
Andrew Thomas, the seventh and the last American astronaut on the
Russian station, and take back all the science instruments and
experiment samples.
</P>
<P>
Discovery will also presented supplies to Mir, including water,
fresh fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
On the benefits of shuttle-Mir program, U.S. NASA officials
said without this program and the many problems troubling Mir, it
would have been difficult to collaborate on the planned
international space station. Besides, it has provided NASA with
long-duration space experience.
</P>
<P>
"The shuttle-Mir program has been very useful in giving our
astronauts good training in crisis management," said James
Sensenbrenner, Chairman of the House Science Committee.
</P>
<P>
All the seven Mir tour by Americans and the total number of
days in space add up to 977, longer than all space shuttle flights
combined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nichols Sentenced to Life in Oklahoma Bombing Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Terry Nichols was sentenced to
life in prison Thursday after refusing to answer questions on how
he helped Timothy McVeigh in the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch imposed the sentence in
Denver after listening to survivors and relatives of victims
describe how the worst terrorist attack on U.S. soil left their
lives in ruins.
</P>
<P>
The 43-year-old Nichols was convicted on December 23 of
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy in the April 19, 1995
bombing that killed 168 people and injured hundreds others.
</P>
<P>
Matsch said Nichols and McVeigh were on a campaign to disrupt
and intimidate the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh, Nichols' Army buddy, was convicted of murder and
conspiracy and sentenced to death last year.
</P>
<P>
Michael Fortier, who was also in the Army with the two men, was
sentenced to 12 years in prison last week for failing to notify
anyone about the bombing plot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Provides Credit for Lesotho Water Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Thursday approved
a 45 million U.S. dollar interest-free credit to support Phase 1B
of the Lesotho Highlands Water Project.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be utilized to finance environmental, social
and technical support to a project which will bring water to South
Africa's water-scarce economic heartland of Gauteng and provide
crucial revenues for poverty reduction and macroeconomic stability
in the small mountain kingdom of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The project will build a 145-meter dam at Mohale, located in
central Lesotho along the Senqunyane River, a 15-meter small dam
on the Matsoku River to the east, and water tunnels from each site
to deliver a combined 11.8 cubic meters of water per second to
Katse Dam.
</P>
<P>
The Katse Dam and an 82 kilometer tunnel system, both built
under Phase 1A, will transfer water to the Vaal River System in
South Africa. These and associated infrastructure components
represents 60 percent of the total project cost.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessional
lending arm for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Pledges to Combat Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
launching tough measures to combat corrupt and collusive practices
in the bureaucracy in a bid to provide public better services and
to create a clean administration, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Government officials at all levels had been ordered to
intensify the campaign to fight corruption, collusion and
nepotism, Coordinating Minister for Development Supervision and
State Administrative Reform Hartarto Sastrosoenarto said here
Thursday after meeting with President B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
"Our priority is to carry out reform in the government and
state administration," the Jakarta Post daily Friday quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto said he would soon issue comprehensive criteria on
what actions constitute corruption, collusion and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
He said government officials were not allowed to use their
authority to grant special privileges and facilities for their
relatives or friends to win government projects.
</P>
<P>
"Special privileges include loans, tax breaks, monopolistic
facilities and the purchasing of state assets against prevailing
regulations," Hartarto said.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, pointed out that relatives of any
government official should not be prohibited from conducting
business as long as they did so without receiving special
privileges from the official.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto also urged the media and the public to join the
campaign against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Habibie promised to improve the image of the
government by combating corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
