<HEADLINE> Austria, Ireland Not to Seek NATO Membership: Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Prime Minister Viktor
Klima and his visiting Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern said that
neither of their countries would seek to join NATO, but both would
like to play a role in Europe's crisis-dissolving efforts.
</P>
<P>
The two government leaders told the press after holding talks
that combating unemployment is a major common task for both
countries and that working out an employment action plan within
the European Union (EU) is "absolutely necessary."
</P>
<P>
The two countries will co-ordinate with one another when
Austria holds the EU presidency in such important fields as
pushing forward the "Agenda 2000," implementing technical measures
for Europe's single currency euro, the EU's expansion and working
out Europe's joint crisis-dissolving efforts.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, who arrived here Wednesday on an official visit, will
return home Friday afternoon. 
</P>
