<HEADLINE> IMF Team to Review Aid Program to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will send a full team to Indonesia next week to evaluate the
continuation of its aid program following Asia Pacific Director
Hubert Neiss's visit to Jakarta last week, an IMF official said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had decided to sent a full team for talks with
Indonesian officials about preparations for the second evaluation
of the IMF aid package to the country, head of the IMF
Representative office for Indonesia Kadhim Al-Eyd, said in a press
release on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team is expected to review the state budget which has
already undergone amendments following the May 13-14 riots and the
replacement of the national leader, said Kadhim.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government and the IMF last April agreed to
several changes in economic indicators which are no longer
relevant to the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Both the IMF and Indonesian officials predicted Indonesia's
inflation at 47 percent and economic growth rate at minus five
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
However, many economic experts predicted Indonesia's inflation
could reach at least 80 percent and the economic growth rate at
minus 10 percent this year following the May 13-14 riots in
Jakarta and the political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The IMF promised last October to provide 10 billion U.S.
dollars of the 43 billion dollar bailout fund which the agency
brokered to bail out Indonesia's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has so far disbursed 4 billion dollars of the 10
billion dollars promised.
</P>
<P>
The second tranche of one billion dollars was initially
scheduled to be handed over to Indonesia on June 4, but delayed
because of the political turmoil which led to the resignation of
former president Soeharto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
