<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank to Protect Baht: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand will intervene
in the foreign exchange markets and increase interest rates to
protect the baht and deter speculative attacks, central bank
governor Chatumongol Sonakul has said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank Thursday increased overnight interest rates in
the bond repurchase market by 100 basis points to 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Friday quoted the governor as saying that
short-term interest rates would likely increase as well.
</P>
<P>
Thursday, the baht was traded at 42.35/45 to the U.S. dollar,
compared with 42.1 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said if the baht remained around 40-45 to the U.S.
dollar, the economy would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
Even so, he added, regulators would use interest rates and
intervention in the foreign exchange markets to smooth
fluctuations, selecting the most appropriate timing to maximize
benefits.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor stressed that the country's foreign
reserves, which stood at 29.5 billion dollars by the middle of
May, were sufficient to allow intervention.
</P>
<P>
Once exchange and inflation rates were stable, the central bank
would inject liquidity into the system, allowing interest rates to
ease, he said.
</P>
<P>
Local businessmen complained that unaffordably high interest
rates have aggravated the liquidity problems they are confronted
with.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said consumer and wholesale inflation indices
remain high. If inflation slowed by 1-2 percentage points, it
would allow the central bank more flexibility to cut interest
rates and boost liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Thailand saw a 10.2 percent inflation rate in May. Under the
fourth letter of intent to the IMF, the country must keep the
inflation rate at 10.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
