<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Subterranean Development in 21st Century China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Qian Qihu, of the Chinese Academy
of Engineering (CAE), said that moving some department stores,
communications facilities, entertainment centers, workshops, and
warehouses below ground in China is inevitable in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qian, an academician of the CAE, explained that making better
use of underground space could take some of the pressure off the
limited amount of land in cities. When a country's per capita GNP
is above 500 U.S. dollars, it has entered an underground space
development phase and, when it goes above 1,000 U.S. dollars,
there will be a boom in underground space development, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's per-capita GNP is now exceeding the 600 U.S. dollar
mark, and in coastal regions, above 1,000 U.S. dollars, so Qian
sees a golden period in the country for subway projects.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that areas below ground should be regarded as
a kind of land resource and their development is an effective way
of guaranteeing continued development in the urban areas.
</P>
<P>
According to forecasts, the number of China's cities is
expected to go from less than 700 at present to more than 1,000 in
the year 2010, and the urban population in the middle of the next
century will be 700 million more than it was in 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
