<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Report Stable Incomes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Most urban and rural residents of
this, China's largest economic and financial center have reported
stable incomes and are satisfied with the current price levels, an
official survey indicates.
</P>
<P>
Some 60.6 percent of the survey respondents say that their
monthly income exceeds 800 yuan (about 100 US dollars). This is
11.2 percentage points higher than the comparable figure the
previous survey found three months ago.
</P>
<P>
About 20.7 percent of those surveyed say their income has
increased over the past three months, but this group is down 3.3
percentage points. The number of people who say that their
incomes have declined rose 1.9 percentage points to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 54.3 percent of the survey respondents say that their
incomes have remained almost unchanged in the past three months,
up 1.7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The survey also finds that Shanghai residents are generally
satisfied with the present price levels, as 78.4 percent of those
surveyed consider that the current price levels are "acceptable and
normal".
</P>
<P>
Those who say that the current price levels are too high
account for 21.6 percent of all respondents.
</P>
<P>
On the future price trend, 67.7 percent of those
surveyed say prices will remain largely stable, up 3.1 percentage
points from the previous survey. Only 14.1 percent of the
respondents expect prices to go up rapidly, down 5.8 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that Shanghai residents have developed a
habit of diversifying their investments, with the first three
investment choices being savings, securities and insurance. The
group of people investing in securities show the most rapid
increase, surging 37 percentage points from three years ago, while
the rate of preference for savings declines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
