<HEADLINE> Steel Market Sets Up Price Index To Curb Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai-based East China
Steel Market has become the country's first institution to set up
a price index system aimed at curbing the dumping of steel
products on the market.
</P>
<P>
Eight companies have been listed as the first group of price
providers, and their prices will be regarded as references for the
clients. These firms are relatively powerful among the 300-plus
market members, each with a weekly transaction of 1,000 tons. The
second group of such companies is to be selected soon.
</P>
<P>
A local expert said that some local steel makers are selling
their products at prices 20 percent lower than the cost. This is
harmful to the industry, which is now in a restructuring period,
featuring low profits and poor efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to become a regional pricing center
for the steel trade, according to an official in charge of the
market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
