<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Advised to Improve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia must have sound
environmental policies if it is to sustain economic growth and
recovery, The Indonesian Observer Friday quoted an official of the
United Nations as saying.
</P>
<P>
The theme of Thursday's World Environment Day, "For Life on
Earth, Save our Seas", is very relevant to Indonesia given that
two-thirds of its territorial area is water, said Rajan, resident
representative of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In this world's largest archipelago, he said, 160 small islands
are ecologically at risk because of global warming and natural
disasters, while heavy sea traffic creates problems related to the
disposal of toxic and hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the National Institute of Sciences shows
that out of the country's 70,000 hectares of coral reefs, 41.78
percent of them have been damaged and only 6.2 percent are in
excellent condition.
</P>
<P>
Reports reveal that about 70 percent of 81,000 kilometers of
the Indonesian coastline has been damaged due to the widespread
and continuing destruction of mangroves that protect shores and
provide a breeding ground for various fish species.
</P>
<P>
Rajan said Indonesia faces a multitude of challenges including
economic recovery and political reforms, but it should be
remembered that significant environmental threats continue to
exist, compounded by the recurring El Nino phenomena, drought and
forest fires.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, while providing support for recovery and reform,
UNDP will also continue to focus on the links between the economic
crisis and environmental protection," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
