<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Station Doing Celestial Research From Roof Of The World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have built the
world's highest observatory in the northern hemisphere, 4,300
meters above sea level on the Tibet Plateau at Yangbajan to do
research that is usually done by satellites and space stations.
</P>
<P>
Tan Youheng, a research fellow at the High Energy Physics
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), said that one
of its major objectives is to study the Milky Way and gamma
sources and gamma ray eruptions at the beginning of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The CAS will cooperate with Japan and Italy in installing a
solar neutron monitor and solar neutron telecopes at Yangbajan to
study high-energy particles in solar flares and to determine the
impact of the solar magnetic field on the earth, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The program, which is expected to be completed by the year
2002, will allow scientists at Yangbajan to make more sensitive
analyses than with the particle detectors on the Alpha space
station.
</P>
<P>
The CAS also plans to welcome cooperation from overseas
scientists in installation of six atmospheric Cerlenkov Imaging
Telescopes of 10-meter in diameter preceding 2010.
</P>
<P>
Cosmic rays come from high energy particles in outer space and
are the only material sample that man can get from the solar
system.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China worked in cooperation with Japan and built a
cosmic ray observation station at Yangbajan in 1990. Tan
acknowledged that the new telescopes and the carpet observation
will make Yangbajan the only station in the world that can study a
cosmic ray in the sub-high-energy region and very-high-energy
region simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The thin atmosphere at the station gives it superior ground
observation conditions.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to invite a large number of well-known
scientists both at home and from overseas to come to conduct
exploratory researches at the station in the first decade of the
next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
