<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian Post and Telegraph Company (ECT)
plans to invest a total of 450.7 million U.S. dollars this year in
its modernization program.
</P>
<P>
The investment is part of a plan to stimulate and expand the
country's telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
It represents a 38.8 percent increase over that of 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean forest products exports will drop 10 to 15
percent with a loss of 200 million to 300 million dollars this
year, president of the National Wood Corporation (Corma) Fernando
Leniz said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the reduction to Southeast Asian financial crisis
as 45 percent of the products used to be destined for the region.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Dutch government has granted Nicaragua 1.9
million dollars in financial aid for its implementation of a
forest development and conservation program.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at protecting the tropical forests and the
natural resources of the "Rio Indio Maiz" biological reserve.
</P>
<P>
Dutch financial assistance to Nicaragua this year is estimated
at 21 million dollars, compared to three million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican industrial exports in the first four
months of this year amounted to 858.64 million dollars, a 14.87
percent increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented 38.8 percent of the country's total
exports, according to data released by the Foreign Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian merchant fleet had 9,388 ships up
to May 28, 1998, a gross tonnage of 114.8 million and an income of
27.7 million dollars, according to Ruben Reyna, general
administrator of the Panama Maritime Authority.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian coffee exports amounted to 910,300
60-kilo bags in April, a 33.4 percent drop from the same period of
last year, because of a reduced harvest this year. 
</P>
