<HEADLINE> World Bank Provides 63-Million-U.S.-Dollar Aid to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved Thursday
a credit of 63 million U.S. dollars to help Bosnia and Herzegovina
introduce key reforms in the management of its public finance.
</P>
<P>
The aid, or the public finance structural adjustment credit, is
the last of eight operations financed by the World Bank during the
current fiscal year to support the reconstruction of Bosnia's
war-ravaged economy, said the World Bank in a press release.
</P>
<P>
"This project constitutes an important milestone in the
country's post-conflict reconstruction program," said Christian
Poortman, World Bank director for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"It represents a move from reconstruction to consolidating
institution and policy reform," he added.
</P>
<P>
Good governance of public finance is a key condition for
establishing the market-driven economy which Bosnia needs to
achieve sustainable growth, according to the bank.
</P>
<P>
The credit for Bosnia will therefore help establish sound
public finance systems and implement reform policies at the state
level.
</P>
<P>
The project's first objective is to help the government prepare
and adopt budgets ensuring that it has adequate funding to meet
its obligations.
</P>
<P>
Other two objectives are: to help develop management capacity
in the country; and to help the authorities address the issue of
transparency and accountability in government budgetary
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
