<HEADLINE> Rains and Locusts Threaten Summer Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- This year's summer grain harvest is
being threatened by rains and locusts, warns today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted experts at the Central Meteorological
Observatory as saying that rain may hit the areas between the
Yellow and Yangtze rivers during the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture has told farmers to cut grain as
soon as possible to the raid of rainfalls. The days around June
10 are normally the busiest time for farmers in the summer harvest.
</P>
<P>
The locust threat is very serious this year, sources at the
Ministry of Agriculture say.
</P>
<P>
Locusts will have matured by the latter part of June and will
then begin to move around. This is precisely the time when summer
grain is being dried outdoors and autumn crops are being planted.
</P>
<P>
This year, locusts are likely to ravage 800,000 ha of farmland
in nine provinces, predicted the ministry.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of China's annual grain output normally comes from
the summer harvest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
