<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Ocean Drilling In South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China will begin its ocean drilling
program next spring in the South China Sea to study climate
changes in East Asia using 30-million-year-old core samples,
according to Wang Pinxian, one of the program's co-chief
scientists.
</P>
<P>
He says it is part of the international Ocean Drilling Program
(ODP) and that China will drill six times between February 16 and
April 11.
</P>
<P>
The deep sea drilling will help scientists understand the
relations between the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and weather changes in
East Asia and may help predict future weather changes.
</P>
<P>
Wang says that one hypothesis has it that the upward movement
of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau causes an eastward movement of warm
moist air from the Indian Ocean, resulting in moist weather in the
southeastern part of China and cold and dry weather in northern
China.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is head of Tongji University's Marine Geology Lab,
says that weather changes on earth are very complicated and need
much more research.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 countries have participated in the ocean study
program. China joined the international Ocean Drilling Program two
months ago. The program's major contribution has been proving the
theory about the earth's plate motion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0320 </DOCNO>
