<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Firm to Launch Large-Scale Human Trials of AIDS Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A South San Francisco-based
biotechnology company will begin the world's first large-scale
trials of an AIDS vaccine this month, the Washington Post
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has given the company,
VaxGen Inc., permission to test its experimental AIDS vaccine
called AIDSVAX on 5,000 American volunteers and 2,500 in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine is a genetically engineered protein almost
identical to one found on the surface of the AIDS virus. In
theory, the vaccine trains white blood cells to produce antibodies
that recognize and attack the same protein, killing the virus.
</P>
<P>
An early version of the vaccine was safely tested on 1,200
humans. A new version, which is made from proteins found on two
different strains of the virus, has been tested on 120 humans, and
this is the one that will be used in the large-scale trials.
</P>
<P>
But there is a mounting consensus that antibodies alone are not
sufficient to stop the virus. A second defense system, consisting
of blood cells programmed to kill other cells infected by the
virus, may be needed.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it could cost more than 30 million
U.S. dollars to conduct such a large-scale clinical trial. About
20 potential AIDS vaccines have been tested on humans, but until
now none has inspired enough confidence to attempt the costly
large-scale trials.
</P>
<P>
VaxGen was co-founded by legendary AIDS pioneer Donald Francis,
one of the first experts to recognize and alert public-health
officials to the coming AIDS epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of today's major Beijing-based newspapers are as follows: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin will visit Hong Kong on July 1
to attend the first anniversary celebrations, marking the region's
return to China.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), Jiang will also attend the opening ceremony of Hong
Kong's new airport and inspect the People's Liberation Army
garrison troops stationed in the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
-- At the invitation of President Jiang Zemin of the People's
Republic of China, President William Clinton of the United States
of America will pay a state visit to China from June 25 to July 3,
1998.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao here yesterday at a regular press conference. Commenting
on US newly released decision to renew China's MFN
(most-favored-nation) status, Zhu said it was a "wise decision."
But he urged the United States to abandon the practice of annual
review of China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), and Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met
separately with Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker of Luxembourg
and his party in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The year's summer grain harvest is being threatened by rain
and locusts, warned Chinese minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang
at a national work conference recently.
</P>
<P>
Chen urged local agricultural officials to put summer harvest
and autumn crop planting at the top of their agenda.
</P>
<P>
-- China will probably face a water crisis by the mid-21st
century if no measures are taken to curb the worsening water
shortage.
</P>
<P>
This warning appears in a report entitled "Water Shortage and
Possible Solutions," drawn up by more than 30 scientists and
experts from the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the Chinese Academy
of Engineering, the Ministry of Water Resources and the Ministry of
Education.  
</P>
