<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Urged to Resist Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress was urged on
Thursday by an influential business group to resist the use of
unilateral trade sanctions against foreign countries as an tool of
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one U.S. laws and executive actions against 36 countries
have been adopted since 1993, the National Association of
Manufacturers (NAM) said in a report.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Congress currently is considering 37 bills that
would impose unilateral economic sanctions of one form or other
against a number of countries, according to NAM.
</P>
<P>
Among those, 26 bills would specifically target 10 countries
while 11 other bills would target unlimited numbers of countries
with economic sanctions, said the report.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, a congressional budget report said existing
economic and trade sanctions have had little impact on the U.S.
economy, less than one billion U.S. dollars a year in lost annual
income on an economy approaching 6.6 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
NAM said that both Republicans and Democrats have equally used
sanctions for foreign policy objects.
</P>
<P>
The group argued that unilateral sanctions do not work and only
clear the way for competitors from Japan or other countries to
pick up more business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
