<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Sets Showdown with Vicario at French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The three-time champion Monica Seles
stunned the world number one Martina Hingis, while two-time
champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario edged fourth-seeded Lindsay
Davenport at the women's semi-finals at the French Open here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Seles, winner of 1990, 1991 and 1992 here,
controlled the situation with her powerful groundstrokes, beating
Hingis 6-3, 6-2 in just 69 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The sixth-seeded American left-hander, playing in her first
tournament since the death of her father and coach Karolj Seles
last month, had never beaten the 17-year-old Swiss teenager in
their five previous encounters.
</P>
<P>
Seles will play Spain's Sanchez Vicario for the title on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez Vicario, the 1989 and 1994 champion, earlier ousted
fourth-seeded American Davenport 6-3, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
"She surprised everyone today," Hingis said after her
defeat. "She played really well. Usually she makes more mistakes
than that, but not today."
</P>
<P>
Referring to her failure to win the title, Hingis
smiled: "Fortunately for me there's always a next year."
</P>
<P>
Hingis, beaten in last year's final by Iva Majoli of Croatia,
had been vying for the only major title that has so far eluded
her, but her loss on Thursday ended her hopes of capturing a
fourth consecutive Grand Slam title.  
</P>
</TEXT>
