<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., EU Agree to Cooperate on Antitrust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
European Union signed an agreement here on Thursday to cooperate
on antitrust investigation that crosses international borders.
</P>
<P>
The plan announced by the Justice Department and the Federal
Trade Commission and the EU outlines how the two sides will refer
antitrust cases to each other, avoiding duplication of costly
investigations and lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
Such cases take on special significance when a country wants to
sue a foreign company, which "may create political friction," said
EU Commissioner Karel Van Miert.
</P>
<P>
As an example, Van Miert noted that Europe recently decided not
to pursue a separate antitrust case against Microsoft Corp., which
the Justice Department sued May 18.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement recognizes that we are truly living in a global
economy, which makes cooperation with other governments
essential," Attorney General Janet Reno said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0344 </DOCNO>
