<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haixia and China Fall to 11th Place at Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Zheng Haixia, Most Valuable Player
when she led China to finish world runner-up four years ago in
Australia, sat on spectator stand, watching Japan playing Germany
in the second classification game of the women's world basketball
championship on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Her Chinese team had been edged by Hungary 95-93 in an overtime
before Japan hammered the host side 88-71.
</P>
<P>
The defeat means China and Haixia, who will play her second
WNBA season for the Sparkers after this dissappointing tournament,
have to settle for 11th place for the first time since the Asian
powerhouse made a world championship debut in 1983.
</P>
<P>
"It's sad," said the 2.04-meter center. "But I don't blame
anyone. We have young players in the team and I wasn't in form."
</P>
<P>
Playing just 22 minutes against Hungary, sixth place finisher
in group E of the second run, the four-time Olympian and five-time
world championship veteran scored 17 points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Dongmei, also a key member of the Chinese team, hit a
game-high 29 points including 7 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
"We played a very close game against Hungary, but in the dying
minutes, they were better than us," said Ma Yuenan, head coach of
China, which trailed 40-45 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
The score was equalled at 83-all with 35 seconds left in the
regulation time on Ma Chengqing's jump which forced an overtime.
</P>
<P>
Center Dora Kalmar-Nagy led Hungary with 20 points, followed by
forward Eva Seres in 17 points.
</P>
<P>
In the Japan-Germany game, the Japanese led all the way to take
a 48-43 halftime lead and then wrap up the victory.
</P>
<P>
Takako Kato scored 27 points for Japan and Mikilo Hagiwara
added 16. German's top scorer was Heiki Roth with 19 points and
six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Japan meets Hungary for ninth place while China takes on
Germany on Friday. 
</P>
