<HEADLINE> Pak Official Visits Quake-Hit Northern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju flew Thursday into
Mazar-e-Sharif along with a consignment of relief goods for
earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
Kanju met with ousted Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani and
other leaders of the Northern Alliance in the northern city and
expressed sympathy on behalf of the government and the people of
Pakistan, according to a report by the Associated Press of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Mazar-e-Sharif, Kanju also visited Afghanistan's
southern city of Kandahar and held talks with the Taliban
leadership.
</P>
<P>
The report did not gave details about the meetings and talks
but said that Kanju's visit is part of Pakistan's efforts to
promote Afghan peace process and keep in contact with all Afghan
leaders irrespective of the political divide.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake measuring 7.1 on the Richter scale rocked
northern Afghanistan last Saturday. At least 3,000 people were
killed and about 50 villages destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
