<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Draws "Road Map" for Iraq to Follow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, executive
chairman of the United Nations Special Commission in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, Thursday gave a
list of priority tasks that Iraq has to fulfill in order to get
sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
The list came after Butler briefed the Security Council of the
United Nations on its technical report on Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction. The brief began Wednesday morning and concluded
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The priority tasks, seen as a "road map" for Iraq to follow to
secure the lifting of the U.N. sanctions against it since 1990,
requires Iraq to meet, fully, its obligations to provide access to
all necessary materials, documents and information concerning the
areas of ballistic missiles, chemical weapons and biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that if Iraq can give the highest quality of
cooperation in this regard, the UNSCOM can present the Security
Council of the United Nations a report in October that will be
quite different from the previous ones, and the UNSCOM can move
its work more faster.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM must certify all Iraq's chemical, biological weapons
and ballistic missiles have been accounted for and destroyed
before the Security Council can consider lifting sanctions that
have been in place since Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who is due to visit Iraq from June 11 to 15, said he
would bring Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz a so-called
"road map" issue that Iraq must still fulfill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
