<HEADLINE> Korean Air Lines to Buy 27 Boeing 737 Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Korean Air Lines has agreed to
buy 27 new Boeing 737 jets at 1.35 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Seattle Times, usually well-informed of Boeing's latest
developments, reported that Boeing and the airline will announce
the order next week, during South Korean President Kim Dae Jung's
state visit to Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
The order would be a boost for Boeing, which said last week
weakening demand from Asia would force it to cut production of its
747 jumbo jet in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some Asian airlines have abandoned plans to buy new aircraft or
delayed deliveries of order since the region's economic problems
began last summer.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Malaysian Airline System confirmed that it has
delayed by three years the delivery of most of the eight Boeing
777s and six 747-400s it was slated to receive this year through
2000. A day later, Taiwan's Eva Airways said it will postpone a
planned 900-million-dollar purchase of six long-range Airbus A340
aircraft and won't make any new aircraft purchases until 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
