<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Suspends 60 High-Speed Trains From Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's rail authorities said
Thursday that they had taken 60 high-speed trains out of service
to undergo a special inspection as a precaution after a train of
the same class derailed Wednesday and killed at least 93 people.
</P>
<P>
The move came after it has been speculated that a broken wheel
of the ill-fated ICE high-speed train may have played a role in
its derailment near the small rail station of the northern German
town of Eschede.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, investigators have found parts of
such a wheel five to six kilometers from the crash site, which
were said to be instrumental to hold the wheel onto the tracks.
Meanwhile damage have also been spotted on parts of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
The German news agency DPA reported that investigators of a
special commission are trying to find out whether the wheel parts
actually belong to the train that crashed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
DPA also quoted survivors as saying that they had heard "a
rumbling noise" several minutes before the accident as well as "an
unnatural rattle" immediately afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Horst Stuchy, president of the German Federal Railway Office
who participated in the investigations, also told the German ARD
television network that a broken wheel might had derailed one of
the 13 cars of the ICE train at a switch point 300 meters before
the crash site and led to the more serious tragedy afterwards.
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed the exact cause had still to be clarified.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rescue workers on the scene are still attempting to
lift slabs of concrete from the wreckage of the train's dining car
where more victims could be found.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 93 people have been confirmed dead,
including two who died of injuries in hospitals Wednesday and
another who died Thursday. Official reports also said 57 people
were still treated in hospitals, including 42 seriously injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
