<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary to Visit Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary William
Daley will take "the most unique" trade mission to the British
province of Northern Ireland Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, Daley said, "I will take what,
in some ways, may be the most unique, and in other ways, the most
important trade mission in my 16 months as secretary."
</P>
<P>
The visit is part of the Clinton administration's strategy to
promote peace in Northern Ireland, where the pro-Ireland
Christians and pro-Britain Protestants have ended a three-decade
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The trade mission to Northern Ireland and the border counties
is a strong statement by the United States government and the 17
business leaders," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a statement of support for President Clinton's strong
commitment to the peace process and to all of the parties who are
working together to bring an end to the instability that has
occurred in Northern Ireland for so many years," he added.
</P>
<P>
Daley's delegation will travel to the Belfast area and to
Sligo, where they will meet with numerous governmental officials,
including Secretary of State for Northern Ireland "Mo" Mowlam.
</P>
<P>
They will meet with local business leaders and have discussions
with entrepreneurs, community leaders and also political leaders
in Northern Ireland, and also with students, business students
specifically.
</P>
<P>
"Our intent is to provide opportunities for these regional
leaders to persuade our delegation that Northern Ireland is a good
place to do business," said Daley.
</P>
<P>
"It is an opportunity for our delegates, many for the first
time, to see for themselves the potential and also the
difficulties of doing business in this part of the world," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was formed by eight Fortune 500 companies and
nine smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
An Irish peace agreement, which was signed in April, was
endorsed by voters in both Ireland and Northern Ireland last
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
