<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Blacks More Likely to Get Death Sentences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Studies found that nearly all
the decision-makers in capital punishment cases in the United
States are white and blacks are far more likely to get a death
sentence than others convicted of similar crimes.
</P>
<P>
The Death Penalty Information Center released a report by
Jeffrey Pokorak of St. Mary's University School of Law in Texas,
which found that in the 38 states that permit death sentences, 98
percent of district attorneys are white. One percent each are
black and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
A two-year study of Perican Bar Association and the United
Nations have found that black jurors have been unfairly barred
from serving on juries in capital cases and that the victims in
the cases are almost always white. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0363 </DOCNO>
