<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Establish Diplomatic Ties With S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will establish
diplomatic relations with Sierra Leone, South African Foreign
Affairs Department said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo Thursday met with
his Sierra Leonean counterpart, Shama Banya, in Ouagadougou,
Burkina Faso, during the Organization of African Unity
ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The department said the decision came after the reinstallation
of the democratically-elected government of S. Leonean President Ahmed
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Nzo assured Sierra Leone's government that South Africa, as
one of the first countries to have condemned the take-over by the
illegal military junta in May last year, will steadfastly
support the government of President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
"Let it be a signal to others that Africa will continue to
reject the illegal seizure of power from governments who have
been democratically elected," Nzo said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that South Africa will establish diplomatic
relations with Sierra Leone as soon as the necessary formalities
have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Nzo committed South Africa to providing some form of
humanitarian assistance to the people of Sierra Leone once the
government there gave him an assessment of its immediate needs.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that we, as a fellow African country,
demonstrate our solidarity with the people of Sierra Leone in a
tangible and meaningful way."
</P>
<P>
Nzo also invited Banya to visit South Africa at a mutually
convenient date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
