<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq May Still Have Biological Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq may still have
biological weapons and nerve gas, Bill Richardson, U.S. ambassador
to the United Nations, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson made the remarks after the Security Council of the
United Nations was given a technical briefing on Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction by Richard Butler, executive chairman of the
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM)in charge of destroying
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Richardson said the briefing by the
UNSCOM showed that "1, biological weapons may be in Iraq today. 2,
VX nerve agent weapons may be in Iraq today. 3, Iraq continues to
play hide-seek with UNSCOM. 4, Iraq is still hiding the documents
that would explain these weapons programs fully."
</P>
<P>
Asked by a reporter whether he still thought Iraq represents a
threat to neighboring countries, Richardson said, "We believe that
Iraq still represents a threat to its neighbors and this is why it
should be contained. And one way it can get out of this morass
that itself has created is to comply with fully with UNSCOM and UN
Security Council resolutions on weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said Wednesday that Iraq has a lot of progress
to make to get the sanctions lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
