<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Impact on Nature Increases: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Negative environmental
trends exist in some countries due to increasing human activities,
according to a report by the Washington-based World Resources
Institute.
</P>
<P>
In its latest report on World Resources 1998-1999 released here
Thursday, the institute said the loss of tropical forests and the
buildup of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere continue unabated
in much of the world. It gave the following details:
</P>
<P>
One third of the world's population already lives in countries
experiencing water stress;
</P>
<P>
An estimated 58 percent of the world's coral reefs are at risk
with Southeast Asia seeing over 80 percent of reefs at risk;
</P>
<P>
The world has lost nearly half of its original forests and
threats continue in the Brazilian Amazon where deforestation rates
reached a new high; and
</P>
<P>
Excessive use of fertilizers and fossil fuels is contributing
to a global glut of nitrogen with nutrient overload threatening
both terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
The institute is a center for policy research and technical
assistance on global environmental and development issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980605.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
